{"title_page": "Heat\u2013Magic rivalry", "text_new": "{{short description|National Basketball Association cross-state rivalry in Florida}}\n{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| name = Heat\u2014Magic rivalry\n| team1 = Miami Heat\n| team2 = Orlando Magic\n| team1logo = Miami Heat wordmark.gif\n| team2logo = Orlando Magic wordmark logo.png\n| first contested = November 28, 1989<br />Magic 104, Heat 99\n| mostrecent = March 4, 2020<br />Magic 113, Heat 116\n| nextmeeting = TBD\n| total = 128<ref>{{cite web|title=Orlando Magic vs. Miami Heat All-Time Head-to-Head Record in the NBA |url=https://www.landofbasketball.com/head_to_head_gl/heat_vs_magic_game_log_season.htm|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n| currentstreak = MIA 3\n| longeststreak =\n* '''[[Miami Heat|MIA]]''': W9\n* '''[[Orlando Magic|ORL]]''': W9\n| series = 71\u201357 (MIA)\n| regularseason = 68\u201355 (MIA)\n| postseason = 3\u20132 (MIA)\n| section_header = Post-season history\n| section_info =\n* '''[[1997 NBA Playoffs|1997 Eastern Conference First Round]]''': Heat won, 3\u20132\n}}\n\nThe '''Heat\u2013Magic rivalry''' is an [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) [[National Basketball Association rivalries|rivalry]] between the [[Miami Heat]] and the [[Orlando Magic]]. It is also known as the '''Sunshine State rivalry''' since both the Heat and the Magic are based in the state of [[Florida]].\n\n==Background==\nThe rivalry started when two teams were expanded into the NBA, both being from Florida which made it a battle for basketball supremacy statewide. Orlando became the first team in Florida to reach the Finals in the 1990s and Miami quickly followed with a strong team of its own after [[Shaquille O\u2019Neal]] left Orlando in 1996.\n\nThe two teams have met just once in the Playoffs in 1997. It was a surprising five-game series that saw [[Anfernee Hardaway]] put in two of the best individual playoff games in team history with back-to-back 40-point performances. The Heat were the better team and prevailed in the decisive fifth game.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rossman-Reich|first=Phillip|title=The Orlando Magic Rivalry That Matters: The Miami Heat|url=https://orlandomagicdaily.com/2018/09/21/orlando-magic-rivalry-matters-miami-heat/amp/|website=[[Fansided]]|date=September 21, 2018|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2010\u20132012: Arrival of LeBron James==\nIn the off season the Heat made headlines nearly every day after it was announced that [[LeBron James]] would sign with the club as a free agent. Other teams in the NBA felt slight and overwhelmed by the amount of coverage the Heat were given.\n\nMagic head coach [[Stan Van Gundy]] was one of the people that noticed the \u201cextra\u201d coverage the Heat had received. Earlier in the year of 2010 at a press conference, Van Gundy stated: \u201cI\u2019m surprised there was enough media left for you guys to get here. ESPN is all Heat, all the time.\u201d\n\nThe players got involved as well. [[Marcin Gortat]] said \u201cHonestly, I\u2019m sick of listening every hour about Miami\u2014Miami that, how great they are, how big they are, what kind of record they gonna have.\u201d\n\n[[Dwight Howard]] chimed in by simply stating \u201cWe\u2019re trying to take their heads off.\u201d Even upper management got involved in the verbal feud.\n\nOtis Smith, the president of basketball operations for the Orlando Magic was discussing LeBron going to Miami and had this to say: \"I was surprised that he went. I thought he was, I guess, more of a competitor.\u201d\n\nEventually LeBron responded to this comment regarding his competitiveness.\n\u201cOrlando, that\u2019s funny that they questioned my competitiveness. I like that. The locker room\u2014we\u2019re going to put a lot of stuff in the locker room...We'll deal with them later.\" <ref>\n[https://bleacherreport.com/articles/504931-orlando-magic-vs-miami-heat-is-this-the-best-rivalry-in-the-nba Orlando Magic vs. Miami Heat: Is This the Best Rivalry in the NBA?], [[Bleacher Report]]. July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter the departure of Dwight Howard from the Magic in 2012, the rivalry has softened but still remains heated amongst the organizations and its fans.\n\n==NBA Playoffs==\n\n===1997 NBA Eastern Conference First Round===\n* Game 1: '''Miami Heat''' 99\u201364 Orlando Magic \n* Game 2: '''Miami Heat''' 104\u201387 Orlando Magic\n* Game 3: '''Orlando Magic''' 88\u201375 Miami Heat\n* Game 4: '''Orlando Magic''' 99\u201391 Miami Heat\n* Game 5: '''Miami Heat''' 91\u201383 Orlando Magic\n\n'''Miami Heat''' win series 3\u20132.\n\n==Common Players==\n* [[Shaquille O\u2019Neal]] Magic ({{nbay|1992|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1995|end}}), Heat ({{nbay|2004|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2008|end}})\n* [[Anfernee Hardaway]] Magic ({{nbay|1993|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1998|start}}), Heat ({{nbay|2007|start}})\n* [[Rashard Lewis]] Magic ({{nbay|2007|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2009|end}}), Heat ({{nbay|2012|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2013|end}})\n* [[Ryan Anderson (basketball, born 1988)|Ryan Anderson]] Magic ({{nbay|2009|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2011|end}}), Heat ({{nbay|2018|end}})\n* [[Jason Williams (basketball, born 1975)|Jason Williams]] Heat ({{nbay|2005|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2008|end}}), Magic ({{nbay|2009|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2010|end}})\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of National Basketball Association rivalries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NBA rivalries}}\n{{Miami Heat}}\n{{Orlando Magic}}\n{{Portal bar|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heat-Magic rivalry}}\n[[Category:Miami Heat]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association rivalries]]\n[[Category:Orlando Magic]]\n[[Category:1989 establishments in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|National Basketball Association cross-state rivalry in Florida}}\n{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| name = Heat\u2014Magic rivalry\n| team1 = Miami Heat\n| team2 = Orlando Magic\n| team1logo = Miami Heat wordmark.gif\n| team2logo = Orlando Magic wordmark logo.png\n| first contested = November 28, 1989<br />Magic 104, Heat 99\n| mostrecent = March 4, 2020<br />Magic 113, Heat 116\n| nextmeeting = TBD\n| total = 128<ref>{{cite web|title=Orlando Magic vs. Miami Heat All-Time Head-to-Head Record in the NBA |url=https://www.landofbasketball.com/head_to_head_gl/heat_vs_magic_game_log_season.htm|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n| currentstreak = MIA 3\n| longeststreak =\n* '''[[Miami Heat|MIA]]''': W9\n* '''[[Orlando Magic|ORL]]''': W9\n| series = 71\u201357 (MIA)\n| regularseason = 68\u201355 (MIA)\n| postseason = 3\u20132 (MIA)\n| section_header = Post-season history\n| section_info =\n* '''[[1997 NBA Playoffs|1997 Eastern Conference First Round]]''': Heat won, 3\u20132\n}}\n\nThe '''Heat\u2013Magic rivalry''' is an [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) [[National Basketball Association rivalries|rivalry]] between the [[Miami Heat]] and the [[Orlando Magic]]. It is also known as the '''Sunshine State rivalry''' since both the Heat and the Magic are based in the state of [[Florida]].\n\n==Background==\nThe rivalry started when two teams were expanded into the NBA, both being from Florida which made it a battle for basketball supremacy statewide. Orlando became the first team in Florida to reach the Finals in the 1990s and Miami quickly followed with a strong team of its own after [[Shaquille O\u2019Neal]] left Orlando in 1996.\n\nThe two teams have met just once in the Playoffs in 1997. It was a surprising five-game series that saw [[Anfernee Hardaway]] put in two of the best individual playoff games in team history with back-to-back 40-point performances. The Heat were the better team and prevailed in the decisive fifth game.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rossman-Reich|first=Phillip|title=The Orlando Magic Rivalry That Matters: The Miami Heat|url=https://orlandomagicdaily.com/2018/09/21/orlando-magic-rivalry-matters-miami-heat/amp/|website=[[Fansided]]|date=September 21, 2018|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2010\u20132012: Arrival of LeBron James==\nIn the off season the Heat made headlines nearly every day after it was announced that [[LeBron James]] would sign with the club as a free agent. Other teams in the NBA felt slight and overwhelmed by the amount of coverage the Heat were given.\n\nMagic head coach [[Stan Van Gundy]] was one of the people that noticed the \u201cextra\u201d coverage the Heat had received. Earlier in the year of 2010 at a press conference, Van Gundy stated: \u201cI\u2019m surprised there was enough media left for you guys to get here. ESPN is all Heat, all the time.\u201d\n\nThe players got involved as well. [[Marcin Gortat]] said \u201cHonestly, I\u2019m sick of listening every hour about Miami\u2014Miami that, how great they are, how big they are, what kind of record they gonna have.\u201d\n\n[[Dwight Howard]] chimed in by simply stating \u201cWe\u2019re trying to take their heads off.\u201d Even upper management got involved in the verbal feud.\n\nOtis Smith, the president of basketball operations for the Orlando Magic was discussing LeBron going to Miami and had this to say: \"I was surprised that he went. I thought he was, I guess, more of a competitor.\u201d\n\nEventually LeBron responded to this comment regarding his competitiveness.\n\u201cOrlando, that\u2019s funny that they questioned my competitiveness. I like that. The locker room\u2014we\u2019re going to put a lot of stuff in the locker room...We'll deal with them later.\" <ref>\n[https://bleacherreport.com/articles/504931-orlando-magic-vs-miami-heat-is-this-the-best-rivalry-in-the-nba Orlando Magic vs. Miami Heat: Is This the Best Rivalry in the NBA?], [[Bleacher Report]]. July 25, 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter the departure of Dwight Howard from the Magic in 2012, the rivalry has softened but still remains heated amongst the organizations and its fans.\n\n==NBA Playoffs==\n\n===1997 NBA Eastern Conference First Round===\n* Game 1: '''Miami Heat''' 99\u201364 Orlando Magic \n* Game 2: '''Miami Heat''' 104\u201387 Orlando Magic\n* Game 3: '''Orlando Magic''' 88\u201375 Miami Heat\n* Game 4: '''Orlando Magic''' 99\u201391 Miami Heat\n* Game 5: '''Miami Heat''' 91\u201383 Orlando Magic\n\n'''Miami Heat''' win series 3\u20132.\n\n==Common Players==\n* [[Shaquille O\u2019Neal]] Magic ({{nbay|1992|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1995|end}}), Heat ({{nbay|2004|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2008|end}})\n* [[Anfernee Hardaway]] Magic ({{nbay|1993|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1998|start}}), Heat ({{nbay|2007|start}})\n* [[Rashard Lewis]] Magic ({{nbay|2007|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2009|end}}), Heat ({{nbay|2012|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2013|end}})\n* [[Ryan Anderson (basketball, born 1988)|Ryan Anderson]] Magic ({{nbay|2009|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2011|end}}), Heat ({{nbay|2018|end}})\n* [[Jason Williams (basketball, born 1975)|Jason Williams]] Heat ({{nbay|2005|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2008|end}}), Magic ({{nbay|2009|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2010|end}})\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of National Basketball Association rivalries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NBA rivalries}}\n{{Miami Heat}}\n{{Orlando Magic}}\n{{Portal bar|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heat-Magic rivalry}}\n[[Category:Miami Heat]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association rivalries]]\n[[Category:Orlando Magic]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat%E2%80%93Magic_rivalry"}
{"title_page": "London Marathon", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Athleticrace\n| bgcolour      = darkred\n| image         = Virgin Money London Marathon.png\n| imagesize     = 200px\n| date          = April\n| location      = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| type          = Road\n| distance      = [[Marathon]]\n| est           = {{start date and age|1981|3|29|df=yes}}\n| record        = Men's: 02:02:37 (2019) <br> [[Eliud Kipchoge]] <br> Women's: 2:15:25 (2003) <br> [[Paula Radcliffe]]\n| homepage      = {{url|http://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com}}\n| current       = Yes\n}}\nThe '''London Marathon''' (currently known through sponsorship as the '''Virgin Money London Marathon''') is an annual long-distance running event held in [[London]], United Kingdom, part of the [[World Marathon Majors]]. The event was first run on 29 March 1981 and has been held in the spring of every year since.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IsgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA92-IA1&dq=London+Marathon#v=onepage&q=London%20Marathon&f=false |title=Runner's World, Vol. 42, No. 1|date=Jan 2007 |page=82 |publisher=Rodale, Inc.|ISSN= 0897-1706 |accessdate=30 September 2010 }}</ref> Since 2010, the race has been sponsored by [[Virgin Money UK|Virgin Money]].\n\nThe most recent edition of the competition was the [[2019 London Marathon]], which took place on Sunday, 28 April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com/en-gb/|title= Home - Virgin Money London Marathon}}</ref> The [[2020 London Marathon]] is set for 4 October, having been postponed from the traditional April scheduling due to the [[COVID-19]] outbreak.<ref>Ingle, Sean (2020-03-13). [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/13/london-marathon-postponed-to-4-october-in-response-to-coronavirus London Marathon postponed to 4 October in response to coronavirus]. ''Guardian''. Retrieved 2020-03-13.</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:London Marathon.png|thumb|Course map.]]\nThe race was founded by the Olympic champion and journalist [[Chris Brasher]] and athlete [[John Disley]]. It is organised by Hugh Brasher (son of Chris) as Race Director and Nick Bitel as Chief Executive. Set over a largely flat course around the [[River Thames]], the race begins at three separate points around [[Blackheath, London|Blackheath]] and finishes in [[The Mall, London|The Mall]] alongside [[St James's Park]]. Since the first marathon, the course has undergone very few route changes. In 1982, the finishing post was moved from [[Constitution Hill, London|Constitution Hill]] to [[Westminster Bridge]] due to construction works. It remained there for twelve years before moving to its present location at [[The Mall, London|The Mall]].\n\nIn addition to being one of the top six international marathons run over the distance of {{convert|26|mi|385|yd|km|abbr=on}}, the IAAF standard for the marathon established in 1921 and originally used for the [[1908 London Olympics]], the London Marathon is also a large, celebratory sporting festival, third in England only to the [[Great North Run]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] and [[Great Manchester Run]] in [[Manchester]] in terms of the number of participants {{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}. The event has raised over \u00a3450 million for charity since 1981,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/news-and-media/news-and-media/why-virgin/ |title=Virgin London Marathon |publisher=www.virginlondonmarathon.com |accessdate=30 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101008070112/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/news-and-media/news-and-media/why-virgin/ |archive-date=8 October 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/world/britain/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9046495 | work=The Economist | title=Give it everything you've got | date=19 April 2007}}</ref> and holds the [[Guinness world record]] as the largest annual fund raising event in the world, with the 2009 participants raising over \u00a347.2 million for charity.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/london/hi/things_to_do/newsid_8617000/8617462.stm |title=BBC&nbsp;\u2013 Your London Marathon guide |publisher=news.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=30 September 2010 |date=25 April 2010}}</ref> In 2007, 78% of all runners raised money.  In 2011 the official charity of the London Marathon was [[Oxfam]].<ref>[http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/2011-virgin-london-marathon-information/official-virgin-london-marathon-sponsors/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324053618/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/2011-virgin-london-marathon-information/official-virgin-london-marathon-sponsors/|date=24 March 2011}}</ref>  In 2014, the official charity was [[Anthony Nolan]], and in 2015, it was [[Cancer Research UK]]. In 2018 it was [[Teenage Cancer Trust]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:20060423 Felix Limo and Martin Lel.jpg|thumb|upright|2006 winner [[Felix Limo]] (left) and 2005, 2007 & 2008 winner [[Martin Lel]] (right).]]\nThe London Marathon was not the first long-distance running event held in the city, which has a long history of marathon events. The [[Polytechnic Marathon]] (also known as the ''Poly'') was first held in 1909.<ref name=PolyHistory>[http://www.kingstonandpoly.org/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=115&Itemid=30 Kingston Harriers, The Polytechnic Marathon, a short history] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009093900/http://www.kingstonandpoly.org/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=115&Itemid=30 |date=9 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe current London Marathon was founded in 1981 by Olympic champion and journalist [[Chris Brasher]] and athlete [[John Disley]].<ref name=VirginHistory>{{cite web | title=Virgin London Marathon&nbsp;\u2013 Background | url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/in-the-beginning/ | accessdate=29 April 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506092528/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/in-the-beginning/ | archive-date=6 May 2009 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Shortly after completing the [[New York City Marathon]] in November 1979 Brasher wrote an article for ''[[The Observer]]'' newspaper which began:\n\n<blockquote>\nTo believe this story you must believe that the human race be one joyous family, working together, laughing together, achieving the impossible. Last Sunday, in one of the most trouble-stricken cities in the world, 11,532 men and women from 40 countries in the world, assisted by over a million black, white and yellow people, laughed, cheered and suffered during the greatest folk festival the world has seen.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/3547639.stm\n|title=The London Marathon story\n|work=[[BBC Online]]\n|date=7 April 2004\n|accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nInspired by the people of New York coming together for this occasion, he asked \"whether London could stage such a festival?\"<ref name=VirginHistory/> The following year Brasher and Disley made trips to America to study the organisation and finance of big city marathons (such as those in New York and [[Boston Marathon|Boston]]). Brasher signed a contract with Gillette for \u00a350,000, established charitable status and outlined six main aims in the hope to mirror the scenes he witnessed in New York and establish the United Kingdom on the map as a country capable of arranging major events. The London Marathon was born.<ref name=\"Flora London Marathon - Background\">{{cite web|title=Flora London Marathon&nbsp;\u2013 Background |url=http://www.london-marathon.co.uk/site/?pageID=2&submenu=12&article=1 |accessdate=6 November 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611044012/http://www.london-marathon.co.uk/site/?pageID=2&submenu=12&article=1 |archivedate=11 June 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe first London Marathon was held on 29 March 1981, more than 20,000 applied to run. 6,747 were accepted and 6,255 crossed the finish line on Constitution Hill. The Marathon's popularity has steadily grown since then. As at 2009, 746,635 people have completed the race since its inception.<ref name=VirginHistory/> In 2010, 36,549 people crossed the line, the biggest field since the race began.<ref>{{cite web | title=Record Numbers Finish Virgin London Marathon | url=http://lrn.london-marathon.com/record-numbers-finish-first-virgin-london-marathon/ | accessdate=30 April 2010 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120715185126/http://lrn.london-marathon.com/record-numbers-finish-first-virgin-london-marathon/ | archive-date=15 July 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The first wheelchair marathon race was held in 1983 and the event was credited with reducing the stigma surrounding disabled athletes.<ref>[http://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/English/Collections/OnlineResources/X20L/Themes/1383/1169/ London Marathon]. [[Museum of London]]. Retrieved on 29 April 2009.</ref> In 2013 the [[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]] Athletics Marathon World Cup was held within the London Marathon featuring athletes of both genders in the T42\u2013T46 and T11\u2013T13 categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/ipc-athletics-partners-london-marathon |title=IPC Athletics partners with London Marathon |publisher=Paralympic.org |date=21 April 2013 |accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref> In August 2013 it was announced that the event would be staged in London until 2017 and feature athletes in the T11-T12, T13, T42-T44, T43, T45-46, T51-52 and the T53-54 class.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishathletics.org.uk/media/news/2013-news-page/november-2013/19-11-13-ipc-marathon/ |title=British Athletics Official Website &#124; New event added to 2014 IPC Athletics Marathon World Cup |publisher=Britishathletics.org.uk |date=19 November 2013 |accessdate=2 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127113429/http://www.britishathletics.org.uk/media/news/2013-news-page/november-2013/19-11-13-ipc-marathon/ |archive-date=27 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFor many years the London and Polytechnic Marathons competed with each other until, in 1996, the latter folded in due to the popularity of the former.<ref name=PolyHistory/>\n\nFollowing the [[Boston Marathon bombings]], organisers of the 2013 London Marathon undertook a review of their security arrangements, despite no specific threats against the event.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.3news.co.nz/London-to-review-marathon-security/tabid/417/articleID/294437/Default.aspx| work=3 News NZ| title=London to review marathon security| date=16 April 2013| access-date=16 April 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613153855/http://www.3news.co.nz/London-to-review-marathon-security/tabid/417/articleID/294437/Default.aspx| archive-date=13 June 2013| url-status=dead}}</ref> A 30-second silence was held before the start of the marathon to show respect and support to those affected by the tragedy.<ref>{{cite web|title=London Marathon: 30 seconds of silence for Boston|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-22237659|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\nThe race is currently organised by Hugh Brasher, son of Chris, as Race Director and Nick Bitel as Chief Executive. Previously [[David Bedford (athlete)|David Bedford]] and Bitel had overseen a period of great change for the race, including amendments to the course in 2005 which saw the cobbled section by the [[Tower of London]] replaced with a flat stretch along the Highway.<ref>{{cite web | title=Flora London Marathon website: ''Marathon History: Course History'' | url=http://www.london-marathon.co.uk/site/marathon_history/index.php?page=2 | accessdate=1 February 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060509113902/http://www.london-marathon.co.uk/site/marathon_history/index.php?page=2 | archive-date=9 May 2006 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Dan Tunstall Pedoe]] was the medical director of the London Marathon for 25 years between the first one in 1981 until 2005. In 2003, Pedoe was shadowed by Sanjay Sharma from St George's Hospital (University of London) who took over the role in its entirety in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p8gDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA116&dq=Medical+cover+at+London+marathon#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Runner's World, Vol. 43, No. 12|page=116|date=Dec 2008 |author=Amby Burfoot|ISSN= 0897-1706 |publisher=Rodale, Inc.|accessdate=1 October 2010 }}</ref> Medical cover is provided by 150 doctors. Also assisting were more than 1,500 volunteers of [[St. John Ambulance]], who organise over 50 first aid posts along the route, and three field hospitals at the finish. St John Ambulance also provide a number of healthcare professions for the event, including nurses, paramedics, ambulances with crews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pponline.co.uk/encyc/london-marathon.html |title=london marathon |publisher=www.pponline.co.uk |accessdate=1 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040813041721/http://pponline.co.uk/encyc/london-marathon.html |archive-date=13 August 2004 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC]] covers the event, devoting rolling coverage for most of the morning. The theme music associated with this coverage, and with the event itself, is called \"Main Titles to The Trap\", composed by [[Ron Goodwin]] for the film ''[[The Trap (1966 film)|The Trap]]''.\n\n[[File:London Marathon at Shooters Hill - wheelchairs - geograph.org.uk - 761541.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Men's Wheelchair competitors at [[Shooter's Hill]], 13 April 2008]]\nThere are three separate groups of starters: Elite Women, Wheelchair (Men and Women), and Elite Men followed by Mass Race.<ref>[http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/accreditation/media/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407185258/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/accreditation/media/|date=7 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Course==\n[[File:Top Three Men at London Marathon 2009 crop.jpg|thumb|The top three men, [[Samuel Wanjiru]], [[Tsegay Kebede]], and [[Jaouad Gharib]], near the end of the 2009 marathon]]\nThe marathon is run over a largely flat course around the [[River Thames]], and spans {{convert|42.195|km|mi|3}}. <!-- Official distance in IAAF rulebook is metric, therefore stated here first. Do ''not'' change the order!--><ref name=\"Highlights-2009\">{{cite episode |title=The 2009 London Marathon Highlights |credits=[[Steve Cram]] (presenter) |network=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |station=[[BBC Two]] |airdate=26 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe route has markers at one mile intervals.  Although the race publicity (athlete advice, timing charts and so on) is mile-oriented,<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/2011-virgin-london-marathon-information/mile-markers/\n|title = 2011 Race information&nbsp;\u2013 Mile markers\n|publisher = Virgin London Marathon\n|accessdate = 28 January 2011\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110119091914/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/2011-virgin-london-marathon-information/mile-markers/\n|archive-date = 19 January 2011\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref> the individual timing splits that are available to competitors after the event are kilometre-oriented.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/race-results/race-results/\n|title = Race results and reports\n|publisher = Virgin London Marathon\n|accessdate = 28 January 2011\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110122091458/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/race-results/race-results/\n|archive-date = 22 January 2011\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nThe course begins at three separate points: the 'red start' in southern [[Greenwich Park]] on Charlton Way, the 'green start' in St John's Park, and the 'blue start' on Shooter's Hill Road.<ref name=\"Route\" /> From these points around [[Blackheath, London|Blackheath]] at {{convert|35|m|abbr=on}} above sea level, south of the River Thames, the route heads east through [[Charlton, London|Charlton]]. The three courses converge after {{convert|4.5|km|abbr=in}} in [[Woolwich]], close to the [[Royal Artillery Barracks]].<ref name=\"Route\">{{cite news |title=Interactive Marathon Map |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/athletics/8011891.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=13 May 2009  | date=23 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Map\">{{cite news |first1=Peter |last1=Storey |first2=Tola |last2=Onanuga |first3=Sam |last3=Murphy |first4=John |last4=Ashdown |title=London Marathon 2009: Mile-by-mile route map |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/interactive/2009/apr/22/london-marathon-route-map |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 April 2009 |accessdate=13 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAs the runners reach the {{convert|10|km|mi|adj=mid|mark|abbr=in}}, they pass by the [[Old Royal Naval College]] and head towards ''[[Cutty Sark]]'' [[drydock]]ed in [[Greenwich]]. Heading next into [[Deptford]] and [[Surrey Quays]]/[[Rotherhithe]] in the [[London Docklands|Docklands]], and out towards [[Bermondsey]], competitors race along [[Jamaica Road]] before reaching the half-way point as they cross [[Tower Bridge]]. Running east again along [[The Highway]] through [[Wapping]], competitors head up towards [[Limehouse]] and into [[Mudchute]] in the [[Isle of Dogs]] via Westferry Road, before heading into [[Canary Wharf]].<ref name=\"Route\" /><ref name=\"Map\" />\n\nAs the route leads away from Canary Wharf into [[Poplar, London|Poplar]], competitors run west down Poplar High Street back towards Limehouse and on through [[Commercial Road]]. They then move back onto The Highway, onto Lower and Upper Thames Streets. Heading into the final leg of the race, competitors pass The Tower of London on Tower Hill.  In the penultimate mile along [[Thames Embankment|The Embankment]], the [[London Eye]] comes into view, before the athletes turn right into [[Birdcage Walk]] to complete the final {{convert|352|m|yd|abbr=in}}, catching the sights of [[Big Ben]] and [[Buckingham Palace]], and finishing in [[The Mall, London|The Mall]] alongside [[St. James's Palace]].<ref name=\"Route\" /><ref name=\"Map\" /> This final section of the route formed part of the [[2012 Olympic Marathon Course]].\n\nSince the first marathon, the course has undergone very few route changes. In the first race, the course took a diversion around Southwark Park before re-joining Jamaica Road on the way to Tower Bridge and was routed through St Katherine Docks past the Tower Hotel, en route to the Tower of London and the cobblestoned stretch of road that in later years was carpeted, to help runners prevent injury on the uneven surface.  In 1982, the finishing post was moved from [[Constitution Hill, London|Constitution Hill]] to [[Westminster Bridge]] due to construction works. It remained there for twelve years before moving to its present location at The Mall. In 2005, the route around the [[Isle of Dogs]] between {{convert|22|and|34|km|mi}} was switched from a clockwise to an anti-clockwise direction, and at {{convert|35|km|mi|abbr=in}} the route was diverted to avoid St Katherine Docks and the [[cobblestone]]d area near the [[Tower of London]]. In 2008, a suspected gas leak at a pub in Wapping diverted the course, but in 2009 the race followed the same path as in 2007.<ref name=\"Guardian history\">{{cite news |first1=Abigail |last1=Gliddon |first2=Tola |last2=Onanuga |title=London Marathon: A brief history |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/apr/24/london-marathon-brief-history |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=24 April 2009 |accessdate=13 May 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Virgin history\">{{cite web |title=History of the London Marathon \u2013 Course History |url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/course-history/ |publisher=London Marathon |accessdate=13 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513081114/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/course-history/ |archive-date=13 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Main|List of winners of the London Marathon}}\n[[File:Paula Radcliffe London marathon 2005 crop.jpg|thumb|[[Paula Radcliffe]], women's winner of the 2005 race]]\nLondon is one of the top six world marathons that form the [[World Marathon Majors]] competition with a  million prize purse.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://worldmarathonmajors.com/UK/about/ |title=World Marathon Majors |publisher=worldmarathonmajors.com |accessdate=30 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423011357/http://worldmarathonmajors.com/UK/about/ |archive-date=23 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The inaugural marathon had 7,741 entrants, 6,255 of whom completed the race.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the London Marathon \u2013 In the Beginning |url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/in-the-beginning |publisher=London Marathon |accessdate=12 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506092528/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/in-the-beginning/ |archivedate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> The first Men's Elite Race in 1981 was [[tie (draw)|tie]]d between American [[Dick Beardsley]] and Norwegian [[Inge Simonsen]], who crossed the [[wikt:finish line|finish line]] holding hands in 2 hours, 11 minutes, 48 seconds.<ref name=\"Eighty-one\">{{cite web |title=1981 Race Report |url=https://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com/en-gb/news-media/media-resources/race-reports/race-report-1981 |publisher=London Marathon |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref> The first Women's Elite Race, also in 1981, was won by Briton [[Joyce Smith]] in 2:29:57.<ref name=\"Eighty-one\" /> In 1983, the first [[Wheelchair racing|wheelchair race]]s took place. Organized by the [[English Federation of Disability Sport|British Sports Association for the Disabled]] (BASD), 19 people competed and 17 finished. [[Gordon Perry (athlete)|Gordon Perry]] of the United Kingdom won the Men's Wheelchair Race, coming in at 3:20:07, and [[Denise Smith (athlete)|Denise Smith]], also of the UK, won the Women's Wheelchair Race in 4:29:03.<ref name=\"Eighty-three\">{{cite web |title=1983 Race Report |url=https://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com/en-gb/news-media/media-resources/race-reports/race-report-1983 |publisher=London Marathon |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[Marathon world record progression|World records for marathon running]] have been set several times. [[Khalid Khannouchi]], representing the United States, set the men's world record in 2:05:38 in 2002. The following year, British runner [[Paula Radcliffe]] set the women's world record in 2:15:25 (later briefly downgraded to \"world best\" by the IAAF as it was achieved in a mixed race,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www1.skysports.com/olympics/story/15234/7256951 |title=Radcliffe to lose records. Marathon queen unhappy at losing world record mark|date=25 October 2011|accessdate=7 September 2013| work=Sky Sports}}</ref> but restored to the title of \"world Record\" shortly thereafter); in 2017 Mary Keitany of Kenya set a world record of 2:17:01 for an all-women's marathon. Previous women's world records were set in 1983 and 1985 by [[Grete Waitz]] and [[Ingrid Kristiansen]] respectively, both of Norway. The current men's course record is 2:02:37 set by Kenyan [[Eliud Kipchoge]] in 2019. [[Kurt Fearnley]] of Australia set the Men's Wheelchair Race course record at 1:28:57 in 2009, and the Women's equivalent was set by American athlete [[Tatyana McFadden]] in 2013, with 1:46:02.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/athletics/london_marathon_2013_american_tatyana_mcfadden_claims_victory_as_shelly_woods_finishes_fifth_1_2161381 |work=East London Advertiser |date=21 April 2013 |accessdate=22 April 2013 |title=London Marathon 2013: American Tatyana McFadden claims victory as Shelly Woods finishes fifth |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413145918/http://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/athletics/london_marathon_2013_american_tatyana_mcfadden_claims_victory_as_shelly_woods_finishes_fifth_1_2161381 |archive-date=13 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Amateur runners==\n[[File:2013 London Marathon at Victoria Embankment (1).JPG|thumb|Amateur runners in the race running along [[Victoria Embankment]]]]\nThe race attracts amateur runners who make up the bulk of the thirty thousand or more participants; commonly running in fancy dress for charity causes. In 2002, [[Lloyd Scott]] completed the marathon wearing a [[deep sea diving]] suit that weighed a total of {{convert|110|lb|kg|abbr=on}}, with each shoe weighing {{convert|24|lb|kg|abbr=on}}; he also set a record for the slowest London Marathon time.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1935471.stm |title=BBC News &#124; UK &#124; Marathon man erodes lead boots  |work=[[BBC News]] |date=17 April 2002 |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] |location=[[London]] |accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref> On 19 April 2003, former boxer [[Michael Watson]], who had been told he would never be able to walk again after a fight with [[Chris Eubank]], made headlines by finishing the marathon in six days. In 2006, Sir [[Steve Redgrave]] (winner of five consecutive Olympic gold medals) set a new [[Guinness World Record]] for money raised through a marathon by collecting \u00a31.8&nbsp;million in sponsorship. This broke the record set the previous year by the founder of the [[Oasis Trust]], [[Steve Chalke]], who had collected over \u00a31.25&nbsp;million. In 2011, Chalke raised a new record \u00a32.32&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oasisuk.org |title=Oasis Trust |publisher=Oasisuk.org |date= |accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref> The \u00a3500 that Claire Squires collected before the race increased to \u00a3920,000 after she died having collapsed during the 2012 race.<ref>{{cite news\n|title= 'Don't stop giving, it's what she would have wanted': Family of 'inspirational' woman who died running London Marathon urge wave of generosity to continue as charity donations rocket past \u00a3780,000\n|first1 = Katherine\n|last1 = Faulkner\n|first2 = Larisa\n|last2 = Brown\n|first3 = Graham\n|last3 = Smith\n|first4 = Rebecca\n|last4 = Evans\n|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2133663/Claire-Squires-JustGiving-London-Marathon-2012-death-girl-ran-Samaritans-memory-brother.html\n|newspaper= [[Daily Mail]] (online)\n|date= <!-- 12:00  --> 25 April 2012\n|accessdate=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nA small number of runners, known as the \"[[London Marathon Ever Presents|Ever Presents]]\", have completed each of the London Marathons since 1981. When the list was first established in 1995, there were 42. After [[2019 London Marathon|2019]], their number has shrunk to 10. At the running of the 2019 event, the oldest runner was 85-year old Kenneth Jones, whilst the youngest runner was 60-year-old Chris Finill. They are all male.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Peel |url=http://www.everpresent.org.uk/ |title=Ever Present Home Page |publisher=Everpresent.org.uk |date= |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Mini Marathon==\nThe Virgin Money Giving Mini London Marathon is the sister of The London Marathon. The course is the last {{convert|3|mi|km|3|abbr=on}} of the London Marathon and is for u13s, u15s and u17s from all 33 London Boroughs along with 13 teams from ten English regions and three Home Countries: Scotland, Wales and [[Northern Ireland]]. There is also a Mini Wheelchair race on the day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minimarathon.co.uk/articles/home/ |title=Virgin Mini London Marathon&nbsp;\u2013 Home |publisher=www.minimarathon.co.uk |accessdate=30 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120903131050/http://www.minimarathon.co.uk/articles/home/ |archivedate=3 September 2012  }}</ref> The race doubles as the British Athletics 3mile Championships.\n\n==BBC live coverage==\nSince 1981, the BBC has broadcast live coverage of the London Marathon.<ref>{{cite web|title=London Marathon to stay on BBC|url=http://sport-onthebox.com/2012/04/20/athletics-london-marathon-to-stay-on-the-bbc-until-2018/|website=Sport on the Box|publisher=Sport on the Box|accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref> The main presenters on [[BBC One]] have been [[Sue Barker]], [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]] and [[Gabby Logan]]. The highlight presenters on [[BBC Two]] have been Jonathan Edwards (2007\u201312), [[Sonali Shah]] (2013), and [[Helen Skelton]] (2014\u201315).  The commentators between for the Marathon on the BBC were David Coleman, Ron Pickering, Brendan Foster, Paul Dickinson, Steve Cram, Stuart Storey, Paula Radcliffe, Dame Tanni Grey-Thompson, Liz McColgan and Rob Walker.\n\n===Theme tune===\nThe theme tune used by the BBC every year is from the film score of ''[[The Trap (1966 film)|The Trap]]'', a 1966 film about a Canadian fur trapper, starring [[Oliver Reed]] and [[Rita Tushingham]]. The music was written by [[Ron Goodwin]] and is performed by the [[Bournemouth Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\"bbcmusic\">{{cite web|title=The Trap - The London Marathon Theme|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/tracks/n2x332|publisher=BBC Music|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"classicfm\">{{cite web|title=Ron Goodwin: The Trap|url=http://www.classicfm.com/composers/goodwin/music/the-trap/|publisher=Classic fm|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship and marketing==\nThe original sponsors of the London Marathon were [[Gillette (brand)|Gillette]], who sponsored the  event from 1981 to 1983. Subsequent sponsors have been [[Mars, Inc|Mars]] (1984\u20131988), [[ADT Security Services|ADT]] (1989\u20131992), [[NutraSweet]] (1993\u20131995), and [[Flora (margarine)|Flora]] (1996\u20132009).<ref name=sponsor>{{cite web |url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/sponsor-history/ |title=Virgin London Marathon |publisher=www.virginlondonmarathon.com |accessdate=30 September 2010 |archivedate=24 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924180210/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/sponsor-history/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GV4q12LtbwMC&pg=PA154&dq=sponsorship+london+marathon+Gillette#v=onepage&q=sponsorship%20london%20marathon%20Gillette&f=false |title=Advertising&nbsp;\u2013 Google Books |publisher=books.google.co.uk |accessdate=30 September 2010 }}</ref> The current sponsors, [[Virgin Money UK|Virgin Money]], have sponsored the marathon since 2010, after signing a five-year \u00a317m sponsorship deal in 2008. On 22 April 2013 the London Marathon renewed its sponsorship deal with [[Virgin Money UK|Virgin Money]] for a further five years and the race changed its name to the Virgin Money London Marathon.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1020056/Branson-signs-17m-sponsorship-deal-London-Marathon.html |title=Sir Richard Branson signs \u00a317million sponsorship deal for London Marathon |work=Daily Mail |accessdate=30 September 2010 |date=16 May 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://lrn.london-marathon.com/static/pdfs/London_Marathon_and_Virgin_Money_announce_new_sponsorship_deal.pdf |title=London Marathon and Virgin Money announce new sponsorship deal |format=PDF |publisher=Virgin London Marathon |date=22 April 2013 |accessdate=22 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423001341/http://lrn.london-marathon.com/static/pdfs/London_Marathon_and_Virgin_Money_announce_new_sponsorship_deal.pdf |archivedate=23 April 2013  }}</ref>\n\nA number of other companies and organisations also use the event for [[brand]] identification and [[marketing]], including [[New Balance]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com/en-gb/|title=Home \u2013 Virgin Money London Marathon|website=www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com}}</ref>  [[Lucozade Sport]]{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}, [[Fuller's Brewery]]{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} and [[Abbott Laboratories]].{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[London Triathlon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|London Marathon}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com}}\n:*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110105161056/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/interactive-map/ Official map - splits given in miles]\n:*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110122091458/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/race-results/race-results/ Results of previous races - splits given in kilometres]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/interactive/2009/apr/22/london-marathon-route-map Interactive Route map from the Guardian (2009 route)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110405084337/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/services/public/paid/sport/london-marathon Historical weather information for marathon days in London]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101212043640/http://www.aubreybooks.com/london-marathon.aspx The Official Register of London Marathon Runners 2001-2010, published by Aubrey Books]\n\n{{London Marathon}}\n{{World Marathon Majors}}\n{{IAAF Gold Label}}\n{{Athletics in the UK}}\n{{Marathons in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Coord|51|28|21.88|N|0|0|34.3|E|scale:25000_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:London Marathon| ]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:April sporting events]]\n[[Category:Marathons in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Athletics in London]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in London]]\n[[Category:Annual events in London]]\n[[Category:World Marathon Majors]]\n[[Category:Sports festivals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Spring (season) events in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Athleticrace\n| bgcolour      = darkred\n| image         = Virgin Money London Marathon.png\n| imagesize     = 200px\n| date          = April\n| location      = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| type          = Road\n| distance      = [[Marathon]]\n| est           = {{start date and age|1981|3|29|df=yes}}\n| record        = Men's: 02:02:37 (2019) <br> [[Eliud Kipchoge]] <br> Women's: 2:15:25 (2003) <br> [[Paula Radcliffe]]\n| homepage      = {{url|http://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com}}\n| current       = Yes\n}}\nThe '''London Marathon''' (currently known through sponsorship as the '''Virgin Money London Marathon''') is an annual long-distance running event held in [[London]], United Kingdom, part of the [[World Marathon Majors]]. The event was first run on 29 March 1981 and has been held in the spring of every year since.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IsgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA92-IA1&dq=London+Marathon#v=onepage&q=London%20Marathon&f=false |title=Runner's World, Vol. 42, No. 1|date=Jan 2007 |page=82 |publisher=Rodale, Inc.|ISSN= 0897-1706 |accessdate=30 September 2010 }}</ref> Since 2010, the race has been sponsored by [[Virgin Money UK|Virgin Money]].\n\nThe most recent edition of the competition was the [[2019 London Marathon]], which took place on Sunday, 28 April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com/en-gb/|title= Home - Virgin Money London Marathon}}</ref> The [[2020 London Marathon]] is set for 4 October, having been postponed from the traditional April scheduling due to the [[COVID-19]] outbreak.<ref>Ingle, Sean (2020-03-13). [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/13/london-marathon-postponed-to-4-october-in-response-to-coronavirus London Marathon postponed to 4 October in response to coronavirus]. ''Guardian''. Retrieved 2020-03-13.</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:London Marathon.png|thumb|Course map.]]\nThe race was founded by the Olympic champion and journalist [[Chris Brasher]] and athlete [[John Disley]]. It is organised by Hugh Brasher (son of Chris) as Race Director and Nick Bitel as Chief Executive. Set over a largely flat course around the [[River Thames]], the race begins at three separate points around [[Blackheath, London|Blackheath]] and finishes in [[The Mall, London|The Mall]] alongside [[St James's Park]]. Since the first marathon, the course has undergone very few route changes. In 1982, the finishing post was moved from [[Constitution Hill, London|Constitution Hill]] to [[Westminster Bridge]] due to construction works. It remained there for twelve years before moving to its present location at [[The Mall, London|The Mall]].\n\nIn addition to being one of the top six international marathons run over the distance of {{convert|26|mi|385|yd|km|abbr=on}}, the IAAF standard for the marathon established in 1921 and originally used for the [[1908 London Olympics]], the London Marathon is also a large, celebratory sporting festival, third in England only to the [[Great North Run]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] and [[Great Manchester Run]] in [[Manchester]] in terms of the number of participants {{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}. The event has raised over \u00a3450 million for charity since 1981,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/news-and-media/news-and-media/why-virgin/ |title=Virgin London Marathon |publisher=www.virginlondonmarathon.com |accessdate=30 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101008070112/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/news-and-media/news-and-media/why-virgin/ |archive-date=8 October 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/world/britain/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9046495 | work=The Economist | title=Give it everything you've got | date=19 April 2007}}</ref> and holds the [[Guinness world record]] as the largest annual fund raising event in the world, with the 2009 participants raising over \u00a347.2 million for charity.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/london/hi/things_to_do/newsid_8617000/8617462.stm |title=BBC&nbsp;\u2013 Your London Marathon guide |publisher=news.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=30 September 2010 |date=25 April 2010}}</ref> In 2007, 78% of all runners raised money.  In 2011 the official charity of the London Marathon was [[Oxfam]].<ref>[http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/2011-virgin-london-marathon-information/official-virgin-london-marathon-sponsors/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324053618/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/2011-virgin-london-marathon-information/official-virgin-london-marathon-sponsors/|date=24 March 2011}}</ref>  In 2014, the official charity was [[Anthony Nolan]], and in 2015, it was [[Cancer Research UK]]. In 2018 it was [[Teenage Cancer Trust]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:20060423 Felix Limo and Martin Lel.jpg|thumb|upright|2006 winner [[Felix Limo]] (left) and 2005, 2007 & 2008 winner [[Martin Lel]] (right).]]\nThe London Marathon was not the first long-distance running event held in the city, which has a long history of marathon events. The [[Polytechnic Marathon]] (also known as the ''Poly'') was first held in 1909.<ref name=PolyHistory>[http://www.kingstonandpoly.org/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=115&Itemid=30 Kingston Harriers, The Polytechnic Marathon, a short history] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009093900/http://www.kingstonandpoly.org/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=115&Itemid=30 |date=9 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe current London Marathon was founded in 1981 by Olympic champion and journalist [[Chris Brasher]] and athlete [[John Disley]].<ref name=VirginHistory>{{cite web | title=Virgin London Marathon&nbsp;\u2013 Background | url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/in-the-beginning/ | accessdate=29 April 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506092528/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/in-the-beginning/ | archive-date=6 May 2009 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Shortly after completing the [[New York City Marathon]] in November 1979 Brasher wrote an article for ''[[The Observer]]'' newspaper which began:\n\n<blockquote>\nTo believe this story you must believe that the human race be one joyous family, working together, laughing together, achieving the impossible. Last Sunday, in one of the most trouble-stricken cities in the world, 11,532 men and women from 40 countries in the world, assisted by over a million black, white and yellow people, laughed, cheered and suffered during the greatest folk festival the world has seen.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/athletics/3547639.stm\n|title=The London Marathon story\n|work=[[BBC Online]]\n|date=7 April 2004\n|accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nInspired by the people of New York coming together for this occasion, he asked \"whether London could stage such a festival?\"<ref name=VirginHistory/> The following year Brasher and Disley made trips to America to study the organisation and finance of big city marathons (such as those in New York and [[Boston Marathon|Boston]]). Brasher signed a contract with Gillette for \u00a350,000, established charitable status and outlined six main aims in the hope to mirror the scenes he witnessed in New York and establish the United Kingdom on the map as a country capable of arranging major events. The London Marathon was born.<ref name=\"Flora London Marathon - Background\">{{cite web|title=Flora London Marathon&nbsp;\u2013 Background |url=http://www.london-marathon.co.uk/site/?pageID=2&submenu=12&article=1 |accessdate=6 November 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611044012/http://www.london-marathon.co.uk/site/?pageID=2&submenu=12&article=1 |archivedate=11 June 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe first London Marathon was held on 29 March 1981, more than 20,000 applied to run. 6,747 were accepted and 6,255 crossed the finish line on Constitution Hill. The Marathon's popularity has steadily grown since then. As at 2009, 746,635 people have completed the race since its inception.<ref name=VirginHistory/> In 2010, 36,549 people crossed the line, the biggest field since the race began.<ref>{{cite web | title=Record Numbers Finish Virgin London Marathon | url=http://lrn.london-marathon.com/record-numbers-finish-first-virgin-london-marathon/ | accessdate=30 April 2010 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120715185126/http://lrn.london-marathon.com/record-numbers-finish-first-virgin-london-marathon/ | archive-date=15 July 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The first wheelchair marathon race was held in 1983 and the event was credited with reducing the stigma surrounding disabled athletes.<ref>[http://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/English/Collections/OnlineResources/X20L/Themes/1383/1169/ London Marathon]. [[Museum of London]]. Retrieved on 29 April 2009.</ref> In 2013 the [[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]] Athletics Marathon World Cup was held within the London Marathon featuring athletes of both genders in the T42\u2013T46 and T11\u2013T13 categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/ipc-athletics-partners-london-marathon |title=IPC Athletics partners with London Marathon |publisher=Paralympic.org |date=21 April 2013 |accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref> In August 2013 it was announced that the event would be staged in London until 2017 and feature athletes in the T11-T12, T13, T42-T44, T43, T45-46, T51-52 and the T53-54 class.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishathletics.org.uk/media/news/2013-news-page/november-2013/19-11-13-ipc-marathon/ |title=British Athletics Official Website &#124; New event added to 2014 IPC Athletics Marathon World Cup |publisher=Britishathletics.org.uk |date=19 November 2013 |accessdate=2 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127113429/http://www.britishathletics.org.uk/media/news/2013-news-page/november-2013/19-11-13-ipc-marathon/ |archive-date=27 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFor many years the London and Polytechnic Marathons competed with each other until, in 1996, the latter folded in due to the popularity of the former.<ref name=PolyHistory/>\n\nFollowing the [[Boston Marathon bombings]], organisers of the 2013 London Marathon undertook a review of their security arrangements, despite no specific threats against the event.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.3news.co.nz/London-to-review-marathon-security/tabid/417/articleID/294437/Default.aspx| work=3 News NZ| title=London to review marathon security| date=16 April 2013| access-date=16 April 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613153855/http://www.3news.co.nz/London-to-review-marathon-security/tabid/417/articleID/294437/Default.aspx| archive-date=13 June 2013| url-status=dead}}</ref> A 30-second silence was held before the start of the marathon to show respect and support to those affected by the tragedy.<ref>{{cite web|title=London Marathon: 30 seconds of silence for Boston|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-22237659|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\nThe race is currently organised by Hugh Brasher, son of Chris, as Race Director and Nick Bitel as Chief Executive. Previously [[David Bedford (athlete)|David Bedford]] and Bitel had overseen a period of great change for the race, including amendments to the course in 2005 which saw the cobbled section by the [[Tower of London]] replaced with a flat stretch along the Highway.<ref>{{cite web | title=Flora London Marathon website: ''Marathon History: Course History'' | url=http://www.london-marathon.co.uk/site/marathon_history/index.php?page=2 | accessdate=1 February 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060509113902/http://www.london-marathon.co.uk/site/marathon_history/index.php?page=2 | archive-date=9 May 2006 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Dan Tunstall Pedoe]] was the medical director of the London Marathon for 25 years between the first one in 1981 until 2005. In 2003, Pedoe was shadowed by Sanjay Sharma from St George's Hospital (University of London) who took over the role in its entirety in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p8gDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA116&dq=Medical+cover+at+London+marathon#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Runner's World, Vol. 43, No. 12|page=116|date=Dec 2008 |author=Amby Burfoot|ISSN= 0897-1706 |publisher=Rodale, Inc.|accessdate=1 October 2010 }}</ref> Medical cover is provided by 150 doctors. Also assisting were more than 1,500 volunteers of [[St. John Ambulance]], who organise over 50 first aid posts along the route, and three field hospitals at the finish. St John Ambulance also provide a number of healthcare professions for the event, including nurses, paramedics, ambulances with crews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pponline.co.uk/encyc/london-marathon.html |title=london marathon |publisher=www.pponline.co.uk |accessdate=1 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040813041721/http://pponline.co.uk/encyc/london-marathon.html |archive-date=13 August 2004 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC]] covers the event, devoting rolling coverage for most of the morning. The theme music associated with this coverage, and with the event itself, is called \"Main Titles to The Trap\", composed by [[Ron Goodwin]] for the film ''[[The Trap (1966 film)|The Trap]]''.\n\n[[File:London Marathon at Shooters Hill - wheelchairs - geograph.org.uk - 761541.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Men's Wheelchair competitors at [[Shooter's Hill]], 13 April 2008]]\nThere are three separate groups of starters: Elite Women, Wheelchair (Men and Women), and Elite Men followed by Mass Race.<ref>[http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/accreditation/media/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407185258/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/accreditation/media/|date=7 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Course==\n[[File:Top Three Men at London Marathon 2009 crop.jpg|thumb|The top three men, [[Samuel Wanjiru]], [[Tsegay Kebede]], and [[Jaouad Gharib]], near the end of the 2009 marathon]]\nThe marathon is run over a largely flat course around the [[River Thames]], and spans {{convert|42.195|km|mi|3}}. <!-- Official distance in IAAF rulebook is metric, therefore stated here first. Do ''not'' change the order!--><ref name=\"Highlights-2009\">{{cite episode |title=The 2009 London Marathon Highlights |credits=[[Steve Cram]] (presenter) |network=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |station=[[BBC Two]] |airdate=26 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe route has markers at one mile intervals.  Although the race publicity (athlete advice, timing charts and so on) is mile-oriented,<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/2011-virgin-london-marathon-information/mile-markers/\n|title = 2011 Race information&nbsp;\u2013 Mile markers\n|publisher = Virgin London Marathon\n|accessdate = 28 January 2011\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110119091914/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/2011-virgin-london-marathon-information/mile-markers/\n|archive-date = 19 January 2011\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref> the individual timing splits that are available to competitors after the event are kilometre-oriented.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/race-results/race-results/\n|title = Race results and reports\n|publisher = Virgin London Marathon\n|accessdate = 28 January 2011\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110122091458/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/race-results/race-results/\n|archive-date = 22 January 2011\n|url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nThe course begins at three separate points: the 'red start' in southern [[Greenwich Park]] on Charlton Way, the 'green start' in St John's Park, and the 'blue start' on Shooter's Hill Road.<ref name=\"Route\" /> From these points around [[Blackheath, London|Blackheath]] at {{convert|35|m|abbr=on}} above sea level, south of the River Thames, the route heads east through [[Charlton, London|Charlton]]. The three courses converge after {{convert|4.5|km|abbr=in}} in [[Woolwich]], close to the [[Royal Artillery Barracks]].<ref name=\"Route\">{{cite news |title=Interactive Marathon Map |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/athletics/8011891.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=13 May 2009  | date=23 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Map\">{{cite news |first1=Peter |last1=Storey |first2=Tola |last2=Onanuga |first3=Sam |last3=Murphy |first4=John |last4=Ashdown |title=London Marathon 2009: Mile-by-mile route map |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/interactive/2009/apr/22/london-marathon-route-map |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 April 2009 |accessdate=13 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAs the runners reach the {{convert|10|km|mi|adj=mid|mark|abbr=in}}, they pass by the [[Old Royal Naval College]] and head towards ''[[Cutty Sark]]'' [[drydock]]ed in [[Greenwich]]. Heading next into [[Deptford]] and [[Surrey Quays]]/[[Rotherhithe]] in the [[London Docklands|Docklands]], and out towards [[Bermondsey]], competitors race along [[Jamaica Road]] before reaching the half-way point as they cross [[Tower Bridge]]. Running east again along [[The Highway]] through [[Wapping]], competitors head up towards [[Limehouse]] and into [[Mudchute]] in the [[Isle of Dogs]] via Westferry Road, before heading into [[Canary Wharf]].<ref name=\"Route\" /><ref name=\"Map\" />\n\nAs the route leads away from Canary Wharf into [[Poplar, London|Poplar]], competitors run west down Poplar High Street back towards Limehouse and on through [[Commercial Road]]. They then move back onto The Highway, onto Lower and Upper Thames Streets. Heading into the final leg of the race, competitors pass The Tower of London on Tower Hill.  In the penultimate mile along [[Thames Embankment|The Embankment]], the [[London Eye]] comes into view, before the athletes turn right into [[Birdcage Walk]] to complete the final {{convert|352|m|yd|abbr=in}}, catching the sights of [[Big Ben]] and [[Buckingham Palace]], and finishing in [[The Mall, London|The Mall]] alongside [[St. James's Palace]].<ref name=\"Route\" /><ref name=\"Map\" /> This final section of the route formed part of the [[2012 Olympic Marathon Course]].\n\nSince the first marathon, the course has undergone very few route changes. In the first race, the course took a diversion around Southwark Park before re-joining Jamaica Road on the way to Tower Bridge and was routed through St Katherine Docks past the Tower Hotel, en route to the Tower of London and the cobblestoned stretch of road that in later years was carpeted, to help runners prevent injury on the uneven surface.  In 1982, the finishing post was moved from [[Constitution Hill, London|Constitution Hill]] to [[Westminster Bridge]] due to construction works. It remained there for twelve years before moving to its present location at The Mall. In 2005, the route around the [[Isle of Dogs]] between {{convert|22|and|34|km|mi}} was switched from a clockwise to an anti-clockwise direction, and at {{convert|35|km|mi|abbr=in}} the route was diverted to avoid St Katherine Docks and the [[cobblestone]]d area near the [[Tower of London]]. In 2008, a suspected gas leak at a pub in Wapping diverted the course, but in 2009 the race followed the same path as in 2007.<ref name=\"Guardian history\">{{cite news |first1=Abigail |last1=Gliddon |first2=Tola |last2=Onanuga |title=London Marathon: A brief history |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/apr/24/london-marathon-brief-history |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=24 April 2009 |accessdate=13 May 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Virgin history\">{{cite web |title=History of the London Marathon \u2013 Course History |url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/course-history/ |publisher=London Marathon |accessdate=13 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513081114/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/course-history/ |archive-date=13 May 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Main|List of winners of the London Marathon}}\n[[File:Paula Radcliffe London marathon 2005 crop.jpg|thumb|[[Paula Radcliffe]], women's winner of the 2005 race]]\nLondon is one of the top six world marathons that form the [[World Marathon Majors]] competition with a  million prize purse.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://worldmarathonmajors.com/UK/about/ |title=World Marathon Majors |publisher=worldmarathonmajors.com |accessdate=30 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423011357/http://worldmarathonmajors.com/UK/about/ |archive-date=23 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The inaugural marathon had 7,741 entrants, 6,255 of whom completed the race.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the London Marathon \u2013 In the Beginning |url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/in-the-beginning |publisher=London Marathon |accessdate=12 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506092528/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/in-the-beginning/ |archivedate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> The first Men's Elite Race in 1981 was [[tie (draw)|tie]]d between American [[Dick Beardsley]] and Norwegian [[Inge Simonsen]], who crossed the [[wikt:finish line|finish line]] holding hands in 2 hours, 11 minutes, 48 seconds.<ref name=\"Eighty-one\">{{cite web |title=1981 Race Report |url=https://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com/en-gb/news-media/media-resources/race-reports/race-report-1981 |publisher=London Marathon |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref> The first Women's Elite Race, also in 1981, was won by Briton [[Joyce Smith]] in 2:29:57.<ref name=\"Eighty-one\" /> In 1983, the first [[Wheelchair racing|wheelchair race]]s took place. Organized by the [[English Federation of Disability Sport|British Sports Association for the Disabled]] (BASD), 19 people competed and 17 finished. [[Gordon Perry (athlete)|Gordon Perry]] of the United Kingdom won the Men's Wheelchair Race, coming in at 3:20:07, and [[Denise Smith (athlete)|Denise Smith]], also of the UK, won the Women's Wheelchair Race in 4:29:03.<ref name=\"Eighty-three\">{{cite web |title=1983 Race Report |url=https://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com/en-gb/news-media/media-resources/race-reports/race-report-1983 |publisher=London Marathon |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[Marathon world record progression|World records for marathon running]] have been set several times. [[Khalid Khannouchi]], representing the United States, set the men's world record in 2:05:38 in 2002. The following year, British runner [[Paula Radcliffe]] set the women's world record in 2:15:25 (later briefly downgraded to \"world best\" by the IAAF as it was achieved in a mixed race,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www1.skysports.com/olympics/story/15234/7256951 |title=Radcliffe to lose records. Marathon queen unhappy at losing world record mark|date=25 October 2011|accessdate=7 September 2013| work=Sky Sports}}</ref> but restored to the title of \"world Record\" shortly thereafter); in 2017 Mary Keitany of Kenya set a world record of 2:17:01 for an all-women's marathon. Previous women's world records were set in 1983 and 1985 by [[Grete Waitz]] and [[Ingrid Kristiansen]] respectively, both of Norway. The current men's course record, which is the second fastest marathon in history, is 2:02:37 set by Kenyan [[Eliud Kipchoge]] in 2019. [[Kurt Fearnley]] of Australia set the Men's Wheelchair Race course record at 1:28:57 in 2009, and the Women's equivalent was set by American athlete [[Tatyana McFadden]] in 2013, with 1:46:02.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/athletics/london_marathon_2013_american_tatyana_mcfadden_claims_victory_as_shelly_woods_finishes_fifth_1_2161381 |work=East London Advertiser |date=21 April 2013 |accessdate=22 April 2013 |title=London Marathon 2013: American Tatyana McFadden claims victory as Shelly Woods finishes fifth |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413145918/http://www.eastlondonadvertiser.co.uk/sport/athletics/london_marathon_2013_american_tatyana_mcfadden_claims_victory_as_shelly_woods_finishes_fifth_1_2161381 |archive-date=13 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Amateur runners==\n[[File:2013 London Marathon at Victoria Embankment (1).JPG|thumb|Amateur runners in the race running along [[Victoria Embankment]]]]\nThe race attracts amateur runners who make up the bulk of the thirty thousand or more participants; commonly running in fancy dress for charity causes. In 2002, [[Lloyd Scott]] completed the marathon wearing a [[deep sea diving]] suit that weighed a total of {{convert|110|lb|kg|abbr=on}}, with each shoe weighing {{convert|24|lb|kg|abbr=on}}; he also set a record for the slowest London Marathon time.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1935471.stm |title=BBC News &#124; UK &#124; Marathon man erodes lead boots  |work=[[BBC News]] |date=17 April 2002 |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] |location=[[London]] |accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref> On 19 April 2003, former boxer [[Michael Watson]], who had been told he would never be able to walk again after a fight with [[Chris Eubank]], made headlines by finishing the marathon in six days. In 2006, Sir [[Steve Redgrave]] (winner of five consecutive Olympic gold medals) set a new [[Guinness World Record]] for money raised through a marathon by collecting \u00a31.8&nbsp;million in sponsorship. This broke the record set the previous year by the founder of the [[Oasis Trust]], [[Steve Chalke]], who had collected over \u00a31.25&nbsp;million. In 2011, Chalke raised a new record \u00a32.32&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oasisuk.org |title=Oasis Trust |publisher=Oasisuk.org |date= |accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref> The \u00a3500 that Claire Squires collected before the race increased to \u00a3920,000 after she died having collapsed during the 2012 race.<ref>{{cite news\n|title= 'Don't stop giving, it's what she would have wanted': Family of 'inspirational' woman who died running London Marathon urge wave of generosity to continue as charity donations rocket past \u00a3780,000\n|first1 = Katherine\n|last1 = Faulkner\n|first2 = Larisa\n|last2 = Brown\n|first3 = Graham\n|last3 = Smith\n|first4 = Rebecca\n|last4 = Evans\n|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2133663/Claire-Squires-JustGiving-London-Marathon-2012-death-girl-ran-Samaritans-memory-brother.html\n|newspaper= [[Daily Mail]] (online)\n|date= <!-- 12:00  --> 25 April 2012\n|accessdate=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nA small number of runners, known as the \"[[London Marathon Ever Presents|Ever Presents]]\", have completed each of the London Marathons since 1981. When the list was first established in 1995, there were 42. After [[2019 London Marathon|2019]], their number has shrunk to 10. At the running of the 2019 event, the oldest runner was 85-year old Kenneth Jones, whilst the youngest runner was 60-year-old Chris Finill. They are all male.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Peel |url=http://www.everpresent.org.uk/ |title=Ever Present Home Page |publisher=Everpresent.org.uk |date= |accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Mini Marathon==\nThe Virgin Money Giving Mini London Marathon is the sister of The London Marathon. The course is the last {{convert|3|mi|km|3|abbr=on}} of the London Marathon and is for u13s, u15s and u17s from all 33 London Boroughs along with 13 teams from ten English regions and three Home Countries: Scotland, Wales and [[Northern Ireland]]. There is also a Mini Wheelchair race on the day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minimarathon.co.uk/articles/home/ |title=Virgin Mini London Marathon&nbsp;\u2013 Home |publisher=www.minimarathon.co.uk |accessdate=30 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120903131050/http://www.minimarathon.co.uk/articles/home/ |archivedate=3 September 2012  }}</ref> The race doubles as the British Athletics 3mile Championships.\n\n==BBC live coverage==\nSince 1981, the BBC has broadcast live coverage of the London Marathon.<ref>{{cite web|title=London Marathon to stay on BBC|url=http://sport-onthebox.com/2012/04/20/athletics-london-marathon-to-stay-on-the-bbc-until-2018/|website=Sport on the Box|publisher=Sport on the Box|accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref> The main presenters on [[BBC One]] have been [[Sue Barker]], [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]] and [[Gabby Logan]]. The highlight presenters on [[BBC Two]] have been Jonathan Edwards (2007\u201312), [[Sonali Shah]] (2013), and [[Helen Skelton]] (2014\u201315).  The commentators between for the Marathon on the BBC were David Coleman, Ron Pickering, Brendan Foster, Paul Dickinson, Steve Cram, Stuart Storey, Paula Radcliffe, Dame Tanni Grey-Thompson, Liz McColgan and Rob Walker.\n\n===Theme tune===\nThe theme tune used by the BBC every year is from the film score of ''[[The Trap (1966 film)|The Trap]]'', a 1966 film about a Canadian fur trapper, starring [[Oliver Reed]] and [[Rita Tushingham]]. The music was written by [[Ron Goodwin]] and is performed by the [[Bournemouth Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\"bbcmusic\">{{cite web|title=The Trap - The London Marathon Theme|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/tracks/n2x332|publisher=BBC Music|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"classicfm\">{{cite web|title=Ron Goodwin: The Trap|url=http://www.classicfm.com/composers/goodwin/music/the-trap/|publisher=Classic fm|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship and marketing==\nThe original sponsors of the London Marathon were [[Gillette (brand)|Gillette]], who sponsored the  event from 1981 to 1983. Subsequent sponsors have been [[Mars, Inc|Mars]] (1984\u20131988), [[ADT Security Services|ADT]] (1989\u20131992), [[NutraSweet]] (1993\u20131995), and [[Flora (margarine)|Flora]] (1996\u20132009).<ref name=sponsor>{{cite web |url=http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/sponsor-history/ |title=Virgin London Marathon |publisher=www.virginlondonmarathon.com |accessdate=30 September 2010 |archivedate=24 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924180210/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/history-london-marathon/sponsor-history/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GV4q12LtbwMC&pg=PA154&dq=sponsorship+london+marathon+Gillette#v=onepage&q=sponsorship%20london%20marathon%20Gillette&f=false |title=Advertising&nbsp;\u2013 Google Books |publisher=books.google.co.uk |accessdate=30 September 2010 }}</ref> The current sponsors, [[Virgin Money UK|Virgin Money]], have sponsored the marathon since 2010, after signing a five-year \u00a317m sponsorship deal in 2008. On 22 April 2013 the London Marathon renewed its sponsorship deal with [[Virgin Money UK|Virgin Money]] for a further five years and the race changed its name to the Virgin Money London Marathon.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1020056/Branson-signs-17m-sponsorship-deal-London-Marathon.html |title=Sir Richard Branson signs \u00a317million sponsorship deal for London Marathon |work=Daily Mail |accessdate=30 September 2010 |date=16 May 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://lrn.london-marathon.com/static/pdfs/London_Marathon_and_Virgin_Money_announce_new_sponsorship_deal.pdf |title=London Marathon and Virgin Money announce new sponsorship deal |format=PDF |publisher=Virgin London Marathon |date=22 April 2013 |accessdate=22 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423001341/http://lrn.london-marathon.com/static/pdfs/London_Marathon_and_Virgin_Money_announce_new_sponsorship_deal.pdf |archivedate=23 April 2013  }}</ref>\n\nA number of other companies and organisations also use the event for [[brand]] identification and [[marketing]], including [[New Balance]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com/en-gb/|title=Home \u2013 Virgin Money London Marathon|website=www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com}}</ref>  [[Lucozade Sport]]{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}, [[Fuller's Brewery]]{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} and [[Abbott Laboratories]].{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[London Triathlon]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|London Marathon}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.virginmoneylondonmarathon.com}}\n:*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110105161056/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/interactive-map/ Official map - splits given in miles]\n:*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110122091458/http://www.virginlondonmarathon.com/marathon-centre/race-results/race-results/ Results of previous races - splits given in kilometres]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/interactive/2009/apr/22/london-marathon-route-map Interactive Route map from the Guardian (2009 route)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110405084337/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/services/public/paid/sport/london-marathon Historical weather information for marathon days in London]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101212043640/http://www.aubreybooks.com/london-marathon.aspx The Official Register of London Marathon Runners 2001-2010, published by Aubrey Books]\n\n{{London Marathon}}\n{{World Marathon Majors}}\n{{IAAF Gold Label}}\n{{Athletics in the UK}}\n{{Marathons in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Coord|51|28|21.88|N|0|0|34.3|E|scale:25000_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:London Marathon| ]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:April sporting events]]\n[[Category:Marathons in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Athletics in London]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in London]]\n[[Category:Annual events in London]]\n[[Category:World Marathon Majors]]\n[[Category:Sports festivals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Spring (season) events in England]]\n", "name_user": "C5FlyingSquad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResults:The London Marathon course record is no longer the second fastest marathon in history, as of September 2019", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_Marathon"}
{"title_page": "Great Retreat (Serbian)", "text_new": "{{short description|Military retreat of the Serbian army during the Winter of 1914/15}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| image       = File:Serbian retreat through Albanian mountains, 1915.jpg\n| image_size  = 300\n| caption     = Serbian retreat through Albanian mountains, 1915\n| conflict    = Great Retreat\n| partof      = [[Serbian campaign of World War I]]\n| date        = 25 November 1915 \u2013 18 January 1916\n| place       = [[Kosovo]] to [[Adriatic sea|Adriatic coast]] through [[Montenegro]] and [[Albania]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|42|22|56.69|N|19|58|51.29|E}}\n| result      = Central Powers victory<br> [[Royal Serbian Army]] is forced into exile\n| territory   = Central Powers capture [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbia]]\n| combatant1  = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Serbia}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|German Empire}}<br>{{flag|Austria-Hungary}}<br>{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Bulgaria}}\n| commander2  = \n| commander1  = \n| strength2   = \n| strength1   = \n| casualties2 = \n| casualties1 = \n}}\n{{Campaignbox Serbia WWI}}\nThe '''Great Retreat''', also known in Serbian historiography as '''the Albanian Golgotha'''<ref name=\"Afflerbarcg120\">{{harvnb|Afflerbach|2006|p=120}}</ref> ([[Serbian language|Serbian]]: \u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0442\u0430),&nbsp;took place during [[Serbian campaign of World War I|the First World War]] following the [[Serbian campaign of World War I|invasion of Serbia]] by the [[Central Powers]].<ref name=\":3\">Hall 2010, p. 46</ref> Facing total destruction but refusing to come to terms, the government and the supreme command made the decision, on 23 November 1915, to retreat through [[Montenegro]] and [[Albania]] where they hoped to reach the Adriatic coast and be rescued by Allied ships.<ref>Hall 2014, p. 280</ref> \n\nThe retreat took the remnants of the Serbian Army, the King, hundreds of thousands of civilian refugees, with thousands of Austrian prisoners, across some of the roughest terrains in Europe in the middle of winter, enduring harsh weather, treacherous roads, and enemy raids. Between November 1915 and January 1916, during the journey across the mountains, around 70,000 soldiers and 140,000 civilians froze, starved to death, died of disease or were killed by hostile, [[Albanian tribes|local Albanian irregulars]]<ref name=\":9\">Dinardo 2015, p. 122</ref> (who resented the repressive policies of the Serbian army towards the Albanian population during the [[Balkan Wars]]).<ref name=\":7\">Pearson 2004, p. 95</ref>\n\nOut of around 400,000 people who set out on the journey, only 120,000 soldiers and 60,000 civilians reached the [[Adriatic coast]] to be evacuated to the [[Greece|Greek]] island of [[Corfu (island)|Corfu]], 11,000 more would die later of disease, malnutrition, or exposure sustained on the retreat.<ref>Hall 2014, p. 279</ref> In some sources published following the conflict, the event was described as the greatest and most tragic episode of the Great War.<ref name=\":5\">Gordon-Smith 1920, p.1</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===Serbian campaign===\n[[File:Centralpowersattackonserbia1915.jpg|thumb|{{Center|Central Powers attack on Serbia, October 1915}}]] \n{{Main|Serbian campaign of World War I}}\nOn July 28, 1914, a month after the [[Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand|assassination of Austrian archduke Franz Ferdinand]], Austria-Hungary, the second-largest country in Europe, declared war on Serbia. Five months later after suffering a third major defeat on the battlefield,<ref>van Ypersele, p. 287</ref> the ancient Habsburg Monarchy was left humiliated by \"the peasant regiments of a small Balkan kingdom\u201d. Franz Ferdinand had not been avenged, with the Dual Monarchy losing twice as many men as the Serbs had. The blow to Habsburg prestige was incalculable and Serbia marked the first Allied [[Battle of Cer|victory]] of World War One.<ref>Schindler 2015, p. 561</ref><ref>War in History, p. 159-195</ref> \n\nIn early 1915, the German chief of the general staff [[Erich von Falkenhayn|von Falkenhayn]] convinced the Austro-Hungarian chief of staff [[Franz Conrad von H\u00f6tzendorf|von Hoetzendorf]] to launch a new invasion of Serbia. In September [[Bulgaria]] signed a treaty of alliance with Germany and quickly mobilized its army. <ref>hall 2014, p 162</ref> On 6 October 1915, combined [[Germany in WWI|German]] and [[Austro-Hungarian Army|Austro-Hungarian]] forces under the command of [[August von Mackensen|Field Marshall August von Mackensen]] attacked Serbia from the north and west with the intention of drawing the bulk of the Serbian forces along the [[Sava]] and [[Danube]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 11 October, without any previous declaration of war, the Bulgarian started making attacks on Serbian border positions;  then on 14 October Bulgaria finally declared war on Serbia, the First and Second Armies under the command of [[Kliment Boyadzhiev|General Boyadzhiev]], advanced into the Timok region of northeastern Serbia<ref name=\":8\" /> with the mission of cutting the vital rail line that ran from Salonika, up the Vardar and Morava River valleys, and depriving Serbia of reinforcements and artillery ammunition.<ref name=\":6\">Sanders 2016, p. 248</ref> Numbering nearly 300,000 men, the forces of Bulgaria quickly overwhelmed the weak Serbian units along the frontier.<ref name=\":8\">Buttar 2015, p.341</ref> The Serbian Army had 250,000 men of which a large number were already battling 300,000 Germans and Austrians in the north. In addition Austrian troops soon started marching from Dalmatia.<ref name=\":2\">Glenny 2012, p.334</ref> \n\nFacing a front of {{convert|1200|km|miles}} against three armies and as promises of aid and reinforcements from the Allies fell through, the Supreme Command of the Serbian Army started an organised retreat towards [[Kragujevac]] and [[Ni\u0161]].<ref name=\":2\" /> On 6 November the Bulgarian First Army, made contact with General Gallwitz\u2019s Eleventh German Army in the vicinity of Ni\u0161, on 10 November they crossed the Morava River about 18 miles south of Ni\u0161 and struck the Serbs. For two days, the greatly outnumbered Serbian army held Prokuplje but eventually had to retreat.<ref name=\":1\" />The pressure of the Austro-Hungarians, the Germans, and the Bulgarian First Army in the north and the Bulgarian Second Army advancing from the east forced the Serbs to retreat in a southwesterly direction into Kosovo.<ref name=\":3\" /> \u00a0\n\n== Prelude ==\n===Kosovo Polje===\n[[File:Serbian front lines at the end of 1915.jpg|thumb|left|{{Center|Frontlines of the Serbian Army between October and November 1915.}}]]\n{{Main|Kosovo Offensive (1915)}}\nIn mid-November, the Serbian armies reached [[Pristina]] ahead of their pursuers but were unable to break south through the blockade of the Bulgarian Second Army, at [[Ka\u010danik canyon|Ka\u010danik]] Pass near [[Skopje]], to reach Salonika and establish the liaison with the French troops of General [[Maurice Sarrail|Sarrail]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe rupture of communications between Ni\u0161-Skopje-Salonika, and the rupture of the liaison with the Allies, brought the army into a most critical situation. [[Radomir Putnik|Field Marshal Putnik]] begins concentrating his troops for the purpose of securing access to the plateau of Gnjilane known as the \"[[Kosovo Polje|Field of Blackbirds]]\"; the region that resonated through five hundred years of Serbian history was the site of a [[Battle of Kosovo|famous battle in 1389]] where the Serbs were defeated by the Turks, and later became the birthplace of Serbian nationalism.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe entire Bulgarian army, supported from the north by parts of the Eleventh German Army, now advanced against the Serbs. Following intense fighting on 23 November Pristina and [[Mitrovica, Kosovo|Mitrovica]] fell to the Central Powers, the Serbian government abandoned [[Prizren]] its last temporary capital in Serbia.<ref>Dinardo 2015, p. 19</ref>   \n\nOnly three possibilities were considered: capitulation and separate peace, final honourable but desperate battle to annihilation, or further retreat. Nevertheless, only two options, retreat, and counter-attack were seriously considered, while the third one, capitulation, was not an option on the table; the Serbian government led by Prime Minister [[Nikola Pa\u0161i\u0107]], [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|Prince Regent Alexander]] and the Supreme Command under Field Marshall Radomir Putnik made the decision to order a general withdrawal and fight on from exile.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe only possible avenue of escape lay to the southwest and northwest, over the towering [[Korab|Korab and Prokletije mountain ranges]] of [[Albania]] and Montenegro, part of the [[Dinaric Alps]], a region of which the mean altitude is over {{convert|6,000|feet|meters}} as the snow began to fall. The Serbian Government planned to reorganise and reform the army with the help and support from the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]]. \n\nOn 23 November, Vojvoda Putnik ordered all Serbian forces to use the last of the artillery ammunition, then bury the cannon, taking breechblocks and sights with them; if burying the guns was impossible, they were to be rendered useless.<ref name=\":6\" />  \n\nOn 25 November 1915, an official order of retreat addressed to the commanders of all armies, was published by the Serbian High Command: \n\n{{Quote/sandbox|text=The only way out of this grave situation is a retreat to the Adriatic coast. There our army will be reorganized, furnished with food, arms, munitions, clothing and all other necessities which our allies will send us, and we shall again be a fact with which our allies must reckon. The nation has not lost its being, it will continue to exist even though on foreign soil, so long as the ruler, the government and the army are there, no matter what the strength of the army may be.<ref>Dinardo 2015, p. 115</ref>|sign=Serbian High Command|source=|title=}}\n\n== Retreat ==\n[[File:Great serbian retreat 1915.jpg|thumb|{{Center|Directions of withdrawal of the Serbian army during the retreat through Montenegro and Albania.}}]]\nThe Serbian Army split into three columns heading towards the mountains of Albania and Montenegro, pursued by the Austro-Hungarian Tenth Mountain Brigade and by the [[German Alpine Corps]].<ref name=\":1\">Dinardo 2015, p. 110<br /></ref>\n\nThe army\u2019s rock-bottom morale was boosted by the presence of the ailing, 71-year-old [[Peter I of Serbia|King Peter,]] who had&nbsp;stepped aside&nbsp; on June 14 to let his son Prince Alexander rule as Regent but now resumed his throne to face the crisis with his people. The elderly monarch, who was almost blind, traveled through the mountains riding in an ox cart.<ref>Pearson 2004, p. 93</ref> \n\nIn order to evade General [[August von Mackensen|Mackensen's]] final encirclement effort, the Serbian army, and a mass of civilians fleeing the massacres perpetrated by Austro-Hungarian troops,<ref>Vickers 1999, p. 88</ref> retreated along three routes, all converged on [[Lake Scutari]], and from there reached the Adriatic.<ref>RTS 2016</ref>\n\n*The Northern Column, took the route across southern Montenegro, from [[Pe\u0107]] to Scutari, via [[Ro\u017eaje]], [[Andrijevica]] and [[Podgorica]].<ref name=\":29\">Dinardo 2015, p. 106</ref> <ref>Sanders 2016, p. 247</ref>\n\nThe group was composed of the First, Second and Third Army and the troops of the defense of Belgrade, it contained the largest contingent of Serbian troops, it also included a mobile medical unit named \"The first Serbian-English Field Hospital\", with two doctors, six nurses and six ambulance drivers, the unit was headed by British nurse and commissioned major, [[Mabel Stobart]].<ref>Stobart 1916, p. 243</ref> The retreat of this force to Andrijevica was to take place under the direction of the First Army, which, with this object, was to occupy positions at [[Ro\u017eaje]]. The mission of the troops of the defense of Belgrade was to cover the retreat of the Army of the Timok as long as that army had not begun its movement of retreat, and then to retire in its turn,<ref name=\":5\" /> because of that the northern column delayed its departure from Pe\u0107 until 7 December. It also had the responsibility to act as a rearguard against an attack by the Austro-Hungarians, Bulgarians, and Germans. Tracing an arc from northwest to southwest through Montenegrin territory and skirting the northern border of Albania, in the snow-covered mountains, hunger, exposure, and disease killed soldiers and civilians, as well as prisoners of war traveling with them, by the thousands.<ref>Dinardo 2015, p. 116</ref>\n\nSerbian officers and artillery crews in Montenegro handed over 30 cannons to the Montenegrin Army,<ref name=\":6\" /> [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] forces played a key role in covering up the withdrawal, most notably against Austro-Hungarian forces in the [[Battle of Mojkovac]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The northern column began to reach Scutari on 15 December.\n\n*The Central Column took the route through central Kosovo across northern Albania, from [[Prizren]] to [[Shkod\u00ebr|Scutari]] via [[Lum\u00eb|Lum]] and [[Puk\u00eb District|Puk\u00eb]].<ref>Hall 2010, p. 46</ref>\nThe central column consisted of the King, the Crown Prince, the administration and the Supreme Command of the Army. Once across the Vizier's Bridge, the troops, who had retreated from Macedonia, would continue west, through Albania, ultimately to Alessio. The Timok Division would also continue to move south and then west through Albania to [[Durr\u00ebs]]. It had the shortest route to the sea but encountered some resistance from hostile Albanians.<ref>Hall 2010, p. 280</ref>\n[[File:Serbian heavy artillery crossing the Babouna River in Macedonia during the retreat to the Adriatic Sea coast 1915.jpg|thumb|{{Center|Serbian artillery retreating}}]]\n[[Essad Pasha Toptani]], an Albanian leader and former Ottoman General, who was a Serb ally, provided protection where this was possible.<ref>Pavlovi\u0107 2014, p. 163</ref> Where he was in control, his gendarmes gave support to retreating Serbian troops, but in more isolated places and as the columns moved to territories in the north, where Essad Pasha\u2019s authority did not hold sway, attacks by Albanian irregulars became commonplace. The previous two Serbian Army invasions into Albania, one in 1913 and the second in May 1915, made many of the locals ready to take their revenge (perhaps also in retribution for Serbian brutality in the First Balkan War).<ref name=\":4\">Kramer 2008, p. 142</ref><ref name=\"Mojzes198\">{{harvnb|Mojzes|2011|p=198}}.</ref><ref name=\"Majstorovic178\">{{harvnb|Majstorovic|2014|p=178}}.</ref><ref name=\"Ramet48\">{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=48}}.</ref>\nRegent Alexander crossed it in just two and a half days, the Serbian government set off on 24 November 15 and reached Scutari four days later, while the officers of the Supreme Command who accompanied the Chief of the General Staff [[Radomir Putnik]] took longer, leaving on 26 November and arriving in Scutari on 6 December.<ref name=\":0\">Mitrovi\u0107 2007, p. 161</ref>\n\n*The Southern Column was sent in the third route of withdrawal, from Prizren to Lum and further through the Albanian mountains to [[Debar]] and [[Struga]].<ref>Hall 2010, p. 280</ref>\n\nThe southern column was the \ufb01rst to depart and the last to arrive at the coast. The southern route presented the most direct way to make contact with Sarrail\u2019s Army of the Orient. The General Headquarters had asked the commanders of these groups to keep in constant telegraphic communication, but from the first day of the operations, this was found to be impossible. The geography of the country did not allow of any other means of communication, so that the commanders of these groups were, during the whole movement, left to their own devices.\n\nAll the troops part of this group were placed under the orders of the commander of the Army of the Timok.<ref name=\":5\" /> The column left on 25 November and moved south all the way to [[Elbasan]]. Along the way it had to contend with Albanian resistance and Bulgarian attacks; on 10 December, the Bulgarians attacked Serbian positions along the crest of the [[Jablanica (mountain range)|Jablanica]] mountain range.<ref>Pearson 2004, p. 94</ref> As the Bulgarians again reached Struga before them, Serbian soldiers and civilians turned southwesterly, marching down the Albanian coast to [[Vlor\u00eb|Valona]] and across via [[Tirana]] reaching [[Durr\u00ebs]] on 21 December. \n[[File:King Peter of Serbia retreating across the Albanian Mountains, 1915.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|{{Center|King Peter of Serbia during the Great Retreat by [[Frank O. Salisbury]]}}]]\nAs early as 20 November, Pa\u0161i\u0107 had sent an urgent message to Serbia\u2019s allies, asking for supplies, particularly food, to be sent to the Adriatic ports, but when the Northern and Central columns arrived in Scutari, they found the harbour empty of the foreign ships they had expected and hoped for. Food had been dispatched from France and Britain, but it was in [[Brindisi]], on the other side of the Adriatic, and the Italians had not allocated more than a few small vessels to transport it on to the Serbs.<ref name=\":8\" /> Some supplies had come ashore in Durr\u00ebs, so the columns of troops and refugees had no choice but to set off on further marches south.<ref name=\":8\" /> Eventually, a decision was made to evacuate the Serbian Army, and its accompanying civilians, to the French-occupied [[Corfu|Greek island of Corfu]] and as far as [[Bizerte|Bizerta]] in [[French protectorate of Tunisia|French Tunisia]].<ref>Thomas, Babac 2012, p. 95</ref> This decision, made primarily by the French and British, did not involve any discussions with the Greek authorities.<ref name=\":8\" /> The French sent their navy and the evacuation started on 15 January; the embarkation was made from three ports, [[Sh\u00ebngjin|San Giovanni di Medua]], [[Durr\u00ebs]] and [[Vlor\u00eb|Valona]].<ref>Gordon-Smith 1920, p. 195</ref>  \n\nOn 14 January the Serbian government, ministers, and the members of the diplomatic corps boarded an Italian ship, the ''Citta di Bari'', for [[Brindisi]].<ref name=\":7\" /> On 6 February the Serbian supreme command and Regent Alexander were evacuated to Corfu, where around 120,000 evacuees had arrived by 15 February, and around 135,000 ten days later. Up to 10,000 evacuees were taken to Bizerta around the same time. The [[Italian Navy|Italians]] took over the majority of Habsburg prisoners, and transferred them to the uninhabited island of [[Asinara]] (off the coast of [[Sardinia]]).<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nMost of the Serb troops had been evacuated by 19 February. The cavalry division was last to embark on 5 April 1916, which marked the end of the operation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Th\u00e9ophile Alexandre Steinlen 25 Juin 1916 - Journ\u00e9e Serbe.jpg|thumb|upright|Serbia Day, organized in [[Paris]] for the benefit of the Serbian Relief Fund on 25 June 1916 to coincide with the approximate date of the first [[Battle of Kosovo]]. Poster by [[Th\u00e9ophile Steinlen|Theophile Alexandre Steinlen]]]]\nAccording to the official statistics from 1919, 77,455 Serbian soldiers died, while 77,278 went missing. The worst fate befell the Southern Column, where approximately 43,000 young boys that would have become conscripts in 1916 had been taken by the Army to join the retreat; within a month approximately 36,000 of them died.<ref>Reader's Digest, 2000</ref>\n\nOf the estimated 220,000 civilian refugees who had set off for the Adriatic coast from [[Kosovo region|Kosovo]], only about 60,000 survived. Those who survived were so weak that thousands of them died from sheer exhaustion in the weeks after their rescue. Because the rock composition of the island made it hard to dig graves, those who died on the journey were buried at sea. Bodies were lowered from French ships into the depths of the [[Ionian Sea]], near the Greek island of [[Vido]]; more than 5,000 Serbs are believed to have been buried this way. The sea around Vido is known as \"The Blue Graveyard\" (''[[Plava Grobnica]]'')\"<ref>Askew 1916, p. 360</ref><br>Field Marshal Putnik traveled to France for medical treatment, where he died the following year.<ref>Buttar 2015, p.</ref> The Serbian Army was subsequently redeployed after Greece entered the war on the Allied side; some six Serbian infantry divisions and one cavalry division would eventually return to serve, playing a key role in the breakthrough of [[Macedonian front|the Macedonian Front]] in September 1917, and the [[Liberation of Serbia, Albania and Montenegro (1918)|liberation]] of their homeland a year later.<ref>Hart 2015, p 189</ref>\n\nThe retreat of the Serbian Army across Albania is considered by Serbs to be one of the greatest tragedies in their nation's history.<ref name=\":5\">Gordon-Smith 1920, p.1</ref>\n\n==Images==\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"140\" caption=\"The Great Retreat\">\nFile:Serbian cavalry crossing the Black Drin River during the retreat to the Adriatic Sea Coast 1915.jpg|Serbian cavalry crossing the Black Drin\nFile:Field Marshal Radomir Putnik, the Chief of the General Staff of the Serbian Army, being carried by bearers across the bridge over the Drin River 1915.jpg|Field Marshal Radomir Putnik being carried by bearers\nFile:Serbian artillery during the retreat to the Adriatic Sea coast 1915.jpg|Serbian artillery during the retreat\nFile:Serbian troops and refugees during the retreat to the Adriatic Sea coast 1915.jpg|Serbian troops and refugees during the retreat\nFile:The Column of the First Serbian-English Field Hospital.tif|The Column of the First Serbian-English Field Hospital\nFile:Serbiancolumnretreat1915.jpg|A column of Serbian soldiers\nFile:Ukrcavanje 1916.jpg|Evacuation of the Serbian army\nFile:Serbian troops in Corfu 1916.jpg|Serbian troops in Corfu, Feb 1916\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Albanian Commemorative Medal|Commemorative Medal of the Great Serbian Retreat]]\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/title/gde-cveta-limun-zut/oclc/958005221&referer=brief_results Gde Cveta Limun \u017dut, (2006)]. A documentary film about the Serbian army's retreat.\n*[[King Peter of Serbia]], (2018). A feature film starring [[Lazar Ristovski]].\n*[[Kre\u0107e se la\u0111a francuska]], A World War I song composed by [[Branislav Milosavljevi\u0107]] in Corfu.\n*[[Tamo Daleko]], A World War I song composed in Corfu.\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Books ===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Alice Askew|author2=Claude Arthur Cary Askew|title=The Stricken Land: Serbia as We Saw it|url=https://archive.org/details/strickenlandserb00aske|page=[https://archive.org/details/strickenlandserb00aske/page/360 360]|year=1916|publisher=E. Nash}}\n*{{cite book|author=Prit Buttar|title=Germany Ascendant: The Eastern Front 1915|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tp-HCwAAQBAJ|date=20 August 2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4728-1355-8}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Marie-Janine Calic|title=A History of Yugoslavia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F16cswEACAAJ|year=2019|publisher=Purdue University Press|isbn=978-1-55753-838-3}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Dinardo|first=Richard L.|title=Invasion: The Conquest of Serbia, 1915|year=2015|location=Santa Barbara|publisher=Praeger|isbn=9781440800924|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9sbloQEACAAJ}}\n*{{cite book|author=Misha Glenny|title=The Balkans: Nationalism, War, and the Great Powers, 1804-2012: New and Updated|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LJqYbknmxjYC|date=5 September 2012|publisher=House of Anansi Press Incorporated|isbn=978-1-77089-274-3}}\n*{{cite boo