g in the Twentieth Century|year=2011|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4422-0663-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=m5bDUFZXQ5sC&pg=PA198&dq=Serbian+army+retreat+albania+revenge#v=onepage|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=Vojislav G. Pavlovi\u0107|title=Italy's Balkan Strategies (19th-20th Century)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=laSxDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA163|date=1 January 2014|publisher=Balkanolo\u0161ki institut SANU|isbn=978-86-7179-082-6}}\n*{{cite book|author=Owen Pearson|title=Albania and King Zog: Independence, Republic and Monarchy, 1908-1939|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3_Sh3y9IMZAC&pg=PA93|year=2004|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-013-0|pages=93\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ramet|first=Sabrina P.|title=The Three Yugoslavias: State-building and Legitimation, 1918-2005|year=2006|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253346568|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FTw3lEqi2-oC&pg=PA48&dq=Serbian+army+retreat+albania+revenge#v=onepage|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=Reader's Digest Association|title=The War to End Wars, 1914-18|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780762102884|url-access=registration|year=2000|publisher=Reader's Digest|isbn=978-0-7621-0288-4}}\n*{{cite book|author=Sanders Marble|title=King of Battle: Artillery in World War I|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0fGcCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA249|series=History of Warfare|year=2016|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers|isbn=978-90-04-30728-5}}\n*{{cite book|author=John R. Schindler|title=Fall of the Double Eagle: The Battle for Galicia and the Demise of Austria-Hungary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ck7wCgAAQBAJ|date=December 2015|publisher=U of Nebraska Press|isbn=978-1-61234-804-9}}</ref>\n*{{cite book|author=Gordon Gordon-Smith|title=From Serbia to Jugoslavia: Serbia's Victories, Reverses and Final Triumph, 1914-1918|url=https://archive.org/details/fromserbiatojugo00gord|page=[https://archive.org/details/fromserbiatojugo00gord/page/195 195]|year=1920|publisher=G.P. Putnam's Sons}}\n*{{cite book|author=Mabel Annie Stobart|title=The Flaming Sword in Serbia and Elsewhere|url=https://archive.org/details/flamingswordins00stobgoog|year=1916|publisher=Hodder and Stoughton}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Nigel Thomas|author2=Dusan Babac|title=Armies in the Balkans 1914\u201318|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2YfvCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT12|date=20 May 2012|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-78096-735-6|pages=12\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|author=Miranda Vickers|title=The Albanians: A Modern History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IzI0uOZ2j6gC|year=1999|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-86064-541-9}}\n*{{cite book|author=Holger Afflerbach|title=The Purpose of the First World War: War Aims and Military Strategies\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l6AFCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT120|year=2015|publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG|isbn=3110435993}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Srpska trilogija (Serbian trilogy)|last=Jakovljevi\u0107, Stevan J., 1890-1962.|date=2003|publisher=Isto\u0107nik|isbn=86-83487-18-0|location=|pages=|language=Serbian|oclc=78922797}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/DAN-SESTI-Rastko-Petrovic/dp/B0089W0WZ4/ref=sr_1_1?keywords=Rastko+Petrovic+Dan+%C5%A1esti&qid=1574280375&sr=8-1|title=Dan \u0161esti (The&nbsp;Sixth Day)|last=Petrovi\u0107, Rastko|date=1961|work=Nolit Bgd.|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=Serbian|asin= B0089W0WZ4}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Plava grobnica (or Ode to a Blue Tomb)|last=Bojic, Milutin|date=2016|publisher=|location=|pages=|language=Serbian|isbn=978-8651511595}}\n*{{cite book|author=Geert Buelens|title=Everything to Nothing: The Poetry of the Great War, Revolution and the Transformation of Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tBDUBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT139|date=16 February 2016|publisher=Verso Books|isbn=978-1-78478-150-7|pages=139\u2013}}\n*{{cite book|author=James Lyon|title=Serbia and the Balkan Front, 1914: The Outbreak of the Great War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vMkfCgAAQBAJ|date=30 July 2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4725-8005-4}}\n*{{cite book|author=Stevan K. Pavlowitch|title=A History of the Balkans 1804-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZGugBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA211|date= 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-90017-7}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.rts.rs/page/stories/ci/Velikirat/story/2525/srbi-na-krfu/2175352/od-srbije-do-krfa--put-albanske-golgote.html|title=From Serbia to Corfu, the path of the Albanian Golgotha|last=Zari\u0107|first=Sladjana|date=2016|website=www.rts.rs|language=sr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}\n* [http://www.odbrana.mod.gov.rs/specijalni%20prilog/135/Odbrana%20246%20-%20Specijalni%20prilog%20135%20-%20Zivot%20u%20okupiranoj%20Srbiji%201915-1918..pdf Life in occupied Serbia 1915 \u2013 1918], Magazine \u2033Defense\u2033, special edition No 135, Miljan Milkich, December 15, 2015. (Serbian)\n* [http://www.odbrana.mod.gov.rs/specijalni%20prilog/136/Odbrana%20247%20-%20Specijalni%20prilog%20136%20-%20Albanska%20golgota%20Srpske%20vojske.pdf Golgotha of Serbian Army], Magazine \u2033Defense\u2033, special edition No 136, Snezana Nikolich, January 1, 2016. (Serbian)\n* [http://www.odbrana.mod.gov.rs/specijalni%20prilog/138/Odbrana-250-Spec%20prilog%20138.pdf In the bosom of Bizerte], Magazine \u2033Defense\u2033, special edition No 138, Snezana Nikolich, February 15, 2016. (Serbian)\n* [http://www.odbrana.mod.gov.rs/specijalni%20prilog/148/Specijalni%20prilog%20148.pdf Corfu \u2013 Island of Solvation], Magazine \u2033Defense\u2033, special edition No 148, Milan Milkic, July 15, 2016. (Serbian)\n \n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great Retreat (Serbian)}}\n\n{{World War I}}\n{{Wars and battles involving Serbs}}\n\n[[Category:Serbia in World War I]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1914]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1915]]\n[[Category:1914 in Serbia]]\n[[Category:1915 in Serbia]]\n[[Category:1915 in Albania]]\n[[Category:November 1914 events]]\n[[Category:Albania in World War I]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Serbia]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Austria-Hungary]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Germany]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Balkans Theatre (World War I)]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Serbia]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Military retreat of the Serbian army during the Winter of 1914/15}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| image       = File:Serbian retreat through Albanian mountains, 1915.jpg\n| image_size  = 300\n| caption     = Serbian retreat through Albanian mountains, 1915\n| conflict    = Great Retreat\n| partof      = [[Serbian campaign of World War I]]\n| date        = 25 November 1915 \u2013 18 January 1916\n| place       = [[Kosovo]] to [[Adriatic sea|Adriatic coast]] through [[Montenegro]] and [[Albania]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|42|22|56.69|N|19|58|51.29|E}}\n| result      = Central Powers victory<br> [[Royal Serbian Army]] is forced into exile\n| territory   = Central Powers capture [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbia]]\n| combatant1  = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of Serbia}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|German Empire}}<br>{{flag|Austria-Hungary}}<br>{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Bulgaria}}\n| commander2  = \n| commander1  = \n| strength2   = \n| strength1   = \n| casualties2 = \n| casualties1 = \n}}\n{{Campaignbox Serbia WWI}}\nThe '''Great Retreat''', also known in Serbian historiography as '''the Albanian Golgotha'''<ref name=\"Afflerbarcg120\">{{harvnb|Afflerbach|2006|p=120}}</ref> ([[Serbian language|Serbian]]: \u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0442\u0430),&nbsp;took place during [[Serbian campaign of World War I|the First World War]] following the [[Serbian campaign of World War I|invasion of Serbia]] by the [[Central Powers]].<ref name=\":3\">Hall 2010, p. 46</ref> Facing total destruction but refusing to come to terms, the government and the supreme command made the decision, on 23 November 1915, to retreat through [[Montenegro]] and [[Albania]] where they hoped to reach the Adriatic coast and be rescued by Allied ships.<ref>Hall 2014, p. 280</ref> \n\nThe retreat took the remnants of the Serbian Army, the King, hundreds of thousands of civilian refugees, with thousands of Austrian prisoners, across some of the roughest terrains in Europe in the middle of winter, enduring harsh weather, treacherous roads, and enemy raids. Between November 1915 and January 1916, during the journey across the mountains, around 70,000 soldiers and 140,000 civilians froze, starved to death, died of disease or were killed by hostile, [[Albanian tribes|local Albanian irregulars]]<ref name=\":9\">Dinardo 2015, p. 122</ref> (who resented the repressive policies of the Serbian army towards the Albanian population during the [[Balkan Wars]]).<ref name=\":7\">Pearson 2004, p. 95</ref>\n\nOut of around 400,000 people who set out on the journey, only 120,000 soldiers and 60,000 civilians reached the [[Adriatic coast]] to be evacuated to the [[Greece|Greek]] island of [[Corfu (island)|Corfu]], 11,000 more would die later of disease, malnutrition, or exposure sustained on the retreat.<ref>Hall 2014, p. 279</ref> In some sources published following the conflict, the event was described as the greatest and most tragic episode of the Great War.<ref name=\":5\">Gordon-Smith 1920, p.1</ref>\n\n==Background==\n===Serbian campaign===\n[[File:Centralpowersattackonserbia1915.jpg|thumb|{{Center|Central Powers attack on Serbia, October 1915}}]] \n{{Main|Serbian campaign of World War I}}\nOn July 28, 1914, a month after the [[Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand|assassination of Austrian archduke Franz Ferdinand]], Austria-Hungary, the second-largest country in Europe, declared war on Serbia. Five months later after suffering a third major defeat on the battlefield,<ref>van Ypersele, p. 287</ref> the ancient Habsburg Monarchy was left humiliated by \"the peasant regiments of a small Balkan kingdom\u201d. Franz Ferdinand had not been avenged, with the Dual Monarchy losing twice as many men as the Serbs had. The blow to Habsburg prestige was incalculable and Serbia marked the first Allied [[Battle of Cer|victory]] of World War One.<ref>Schindler 2015, p. 561</ref><ref>War in History, p. 159-195</ref> \n\nIn early 1915, the German chief of the general staff [[Erich von Falkenhayn|von Falkenhayn]] convinced the Austro-Hungarian chief of staff [[Franz Conrad von H\u00f6tzendorf|von Hoetzendorf]] to launch a new invasion of Serbia. In September [[Bulgaria]] signed a treaty of alliance with Germany and quickly mobilized its army. <ref>hall 2014, p 162</ref> On 6 October 1915, combined [[Germany in WWI|German]] and [[Austro-Hungarian Army|Austro-Hungarian]] forces under the command of [[August von Mackensen|Field Marshall August von Mackensen]] attacked Serbia from the north and west with the intention of drawing the bulk of the Serbian forces along the [[Sava]] and [[Danube]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 11 October, without any previous declaration of war, the Bulgarian started making attacks on Serbian border positions;  then on 14 October Bulgaria finally declared war on Serbia, the First and Second Armies under the command of [[Kliment Boyadzhiev|General Boyadzhiev]], advanced into the Timok region of northeastern Serbia<ref name=\":8\" /> with the mission of cutting the vital rail line that ran from Salonika, up the Vardar and Morava River valleys, and depriving Serbia of reinforcements and artillery ammunition.<ref name=\":6\">Sanders 2016, p. 248</ref> Numbering nearly 300,000 men, the forces of Bulgaria quickly overwhelmed the weak Serbian units along the frontier.<ref name=\":8\">Buttar 2015, p.341</ref> The Serbian Army had 250,000 men of which a large number were already battling 300,000 Germans and Austrians in the north. In addition Austrian troops soon started marching from Dalmatia.<ref name=\":2\">Glenny 2012, p.334</ref> \n\nFacing a front of {{convert|1200|km|miles}} against three armies and as promises of aid and reinforcements from the Allies fell through, the Supreme Command of the Serbian Army started an organised retreat towards [[Kragujevac]] and [[Ni\u0161]].<ref name=\":2\" /> On 6 November the Bulgarian First Army, made contact with General Gallwitz\u2019s Eleventh German Army in the vicinity of Ni\u0161, on 10 November they crossed the Morava River about 18 miles south of Ni\u0161 and struck the Serbs. For two days, the greatly outnumbered Serbian army held Prokuplje but eventually had to retreat.<ref name=\":1\" />The pressure of the Austro-Hungarians, the Germans, and the Bulgarian First Army in the north and the Bulgarian Second Army advancing from the east forced the Serbs to retreat in a southwesterly direction into Kosovo.<ref name=\":3\" /> \u00a0\n\n== Prelude ==\n===Kosovo Polje===\n[[File:Serbian front lines at the end of 1915.jpg|thumb|left|{{Center|Frontlines of the Serbian Army between October and November 1915.}}]]\n{{Main|Kosovo Offensive (1915)}}\nIn mid-November, the Serbian armies reached [[Pristina]] ahead of their pursuers but were unable to break south through the blockade of the Bulgarian Second Army, at [[Ka\u010danik canyon|Ka\u010danik]] Pass near [[Skopje]], to reach Salonika and establish the liaison with the French troops of General [[Maurice Sarrail|Sarrail]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe rupture of communications between Ni\u0161-Skopje-Salonika, and the rupture of the liaison with the Allies, brought the army into a most critical situation. [[Radomir Putnik|Field Marshal Putnik]] begins concentrating his troops for the purpose of securing access to the plateau of Gnjilane known as the \"[[Kosovo Polje|Field of Blackbirds]]\"; the region that resonated through five hundred years of Serbian history was the site of a [[Battle of Kosovo|famous battle in 1389]] where the Serbs were defeated by the Turks, and later became the birthplace of Serbian nationalism.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe entire Bulgarian army, supported from the north by parts of the Eleventh German Army, now advanced against the Serbs. Following intense fighting on 23 November Pristina and [[Mitrovica, Kosovo|Mitrovica]] fell to the Central Powers, the Serbian government abandoned [[Prizren]] its last temporary capital in Serbia.<ref>Dinardo 2015, p. 19</ref>   \n\nOnly three possibilities were considered: capitulation and separate peace, final honourable but desperate battle to annihilation, or further retreat. Nevertheless, only two options, retreat, and counter-attack were seriously considered, while the third one, capitulation, was not an option on the table; the Serbian government led by Prime Minister [[Nikola Pa\u0161i\u0107]], [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|Prince Regent Alexander]] and the Supreme Command under Field Marshall Radomir Putnik made the decision to order a general withdrawal and fight on from exile.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe only possible avenue of escape lay to the southwest and northwest, over the towering [[Korab|Korab and Prokletije mountain ranges]] of [[Albania]] and Montenegro, part of the [[Dinaric Alps]], a region of which the mean altitude is over {{convert|6,000|feet|meters}} as the snow began to fall. The Serbian Government planned to reorganise and reform the army with the help and support from the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]]. \n\nOn 23 November, Vojvoda Putnik ordered all Serbian forces to use the last of the artillery ammunition, then bury the cannon, taking breechblocks and sights with them; if burying the guns was impossible, they were to be rendered useless.<ref name=\":6\" />  \n\nOn 25 November 1915, an official order of retreat addressed to the commanders of all armies, was published by the Serbian High Command: \n\n{{Quote/sandbox|text=The only way out of this grave situation is a retreat to the Adriatic coast. There our army will be reorganized, furnished with food, arms, munitions, clothing and all other necessities which our allies will send us, and we shall again be a fact with which our allies must reckon. The nation has not lost its being, it will continue to exist even though on foreign soil, so long as the ruler, the government and the army are there, no matter what the strength of the army may be.<ref>Dinardo 2015, p. 115</ref>|sign=Serbian High Command|source=|title=}}\n\n== Retreat ==\n[[File:Great serbian retreat 1915.jpg|thumb|{{Center|Directions of withdrawal of the Serbian army during the retreat through Montenegro and Albania.}}]]\nThe Serbian Army split into three columns heading towards the mountains of Albania and Montenegro, pursued by the Austro-Hungarian Tenth Mountain Brigade and by the [[German Alpine Corps]].<ref name=\":1\">Dinardo 2015, p. 110<br /></ref>\n\nThe army\u2019s rock-bottom morale was boosted by the presence of the ailing, 71-year-old [[Peter I of Serbia|King Peter,]] who had&nbsp;stepped aside&nbsp; on June 14 to let his son Prince Alexander rule as Regent but now resumed his throne to face the crisis with his people. The elderly monarch, who was almost blind, traveled through the mountains riding in an ox cart.<ref>Pearson 2004, p. 93</ref> \n\nIn order to evade General [[August von Mackensen|Mackensen's]] final encirclement effort, the Serbian army, and a mass of civilians fleeing the massacres perpetrated by Austro-Hungarian troops,<ref>Vickers 1999, p. 88</ref> retreated along three routes, all converged on [[Lake Scutari]], and from there reached the Adriatic.<ref>RTS 2016</ref>\n\n*The Northern Column, took the route across southern Montenegro, from [[Pe\u0107]] to Scutari, via [[Ro\u017eaje]], [[Andrijevica]] and [[Podgorica]].<ref name=\":9\">Dinardo 2015, p. 106</ref> <ref>Sanders 2016, p. 247</ref>\n\nThe group was composed of the First, Second and Third Army and the troops of the defense of Belgrade, it contained the largest contingent of Serbian troops, it also included a mobile medical unit named \"The first Serbian-English Field Hospital\", with two doctors, six nurses and six ambulance drivers, the unit was headed by British nurse and commissioned major, [[Mabel Stobart]].<ref>Stobart 1916, p. 243</ref> The retreat of this force to Andrijevica was to take place under the direction of the First Army, which, with this object, was to occupy positions at [[Ro\u017eaje]]. The mission of the troops of the defense of Belgrade was to cover the retreat of the Army of the Timok as long as that army had not begun its movement of retreat, and then to retire in its turn,<ref name=\":5\" /> because of that the northern column delayed its departure from Pe\u0107 until 7 December. It also had the responsibility to act as a rearguard against an attack by the Austro-Hungarians, Bulgarians, and Germans. Tracing an arc from northwest to southwest through Montenegrin territory and skirting the northern border of Albania, in the snow-covered mountains, hunger, exposure, and disease killed soldiers and civilians, as well as prisoners of war traveling with them, by the thousands.<ref>Dinardo 2015, p. 116</ref>\n\nSerbian officers and artillery crews in Montenegro handed over 30 cannons to the Montenegrin Army,<ref name=\":6\" /> [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] forces played a key role in covering up the withdrawal, most notably against Austro-Hungarian forces in the [[Battle of Mojkovac]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The northern column began to reach Scutari on 15 December.\n\n*The Central Column took the route through central Kosovo across northern Albania, from [[Prizren]] to [[Shkod\u00ebr|Scutari]] via [[Lum\u00eb|Lum]] and [[Puk\u00eb District|Puk\u00eb]].<ref>Hall 2010, p. 46</ref>\nThe central column consisted of the King, the Crown Prince, the administration and the Supreme Command of the Army. Once across the Vizier's Bridge, the troops, who had retreated from Macedonia, would continue west, through Albania, ultimately to Alessio. The Timok Division would also continue to move south and then west through Albania to [[Durr\u00ebs]]. It had the shortest route to the sea but encountered some resistance from hostile Albanians.<ref>Hall 2010, p. 280</ref>\n[[File:Serbian heavy artillery crossing the Babouna River in Macedonia during the retreat to the Adriatic Sea coast 1915.jpg|thumb|{{Center|Serbian artillery retreating}}]]\n[[Essad Pasha Toptani]], an Albanian leader and former Ottoman General, who was a Serb ally, provided protection where this was possible.<ref>Pavlovi\u0107 2014, p. 163</ref> Where he was in control, his gendarmes gave support to retreating Serbian troops, but in more isolated places and as the columns moved to territories in the north, where Essad Pasha\u2019s authority did not hold sway, attacks by Albanian irregulars became commonplace. The previous two Serbian Army invasions into Albania, one in 1913 and the second in May 1915, made many of the locals ready to take their revenge (perhaps also in retribution for Serbian brutality in the First Balkan War).<ref name=\":4\">Kramer 2008, p. 142</ref><ref name=\"Mojzes198\">{{harvnb|Mojzes|2011|p=198}}.</ref><ref name=\"Majstorovic178\">{{harvnb|Majstorovic|2014|p=178}}.</ref><ref name=\"Ramet48\">{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=48}}.</ref>\nRegent Alexander crossed it in just two and a half days, the Serbian government set off on 24 November 15 and reached Scutari four days later, while the officers of the Supreme Command who accompanied the Chief of the General Staff [[Radomir Putnik]] took longer, leaving on 26 November and arriving in Scutari on 6 December.<ref name=\":0\">Mitrovi\u0107 2007, p. 161</ref>\n\n*The Southern Column was sent in the third route of withdrawal, from Prizren to Lum and further through the Albanian mountains to [[Debar]] and [[Struga]].<ref>Hall 2010, p. 280</ref>\n\nThe southern column was the \ufb01rst to depart and the last to arrive at the coast. The southern route presented the most direct way to make contact with Sarrail\u2019s Army of the Orient. The General Headquarters had asked the commanders of these groups to keep in constant telegraphic communication, but from the first day of the operations, this was found to be impossible. The geography of the country did not allow of any other means of communication, so that the commanders of these groups were, during the whole movement, left to their own devices.\n\nAll the troops part of this group were placed under the orders of the commander of the Army of the Timok.<ref name=\":5\" /> The column left on 25 November and moved south all the way to [[Elbasan]]. Along the way it had to contend with Albanian resistance and Bulgarian attacks; on 10 December, the Bulgarians attacked Serbian positions along the crest of the [[Jablanica (mountain range)|Jablanica]] mountain range.<ref>Pearson 2004, p. 94</ref> As the Bulgarians again reached Struga before them, Serbian soldiers and civilians turned southwesterly, marching down the Albanian coast to [[Vlor\u00eb|Valona]] and across via [[Tirana]] reaching [[Durr\u00ebs]] on 21 December. \n[[File:King Peter of Serbia retreating across the Albanian Mountains, 1915.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|{{Center|King Peter of Serbia during the Great Retreat by [[Frank O. Salisbury]]}}]]\nAs early as 20 November, Pa\u0161i\u0107 had sent an urgent message to Serbia\u2019s allies, asking for supplies, particularly food, to be sent to the Adriatic ports, but when the Northern and Central columns arrived in Scutari, they found the harbour empty of the foreign ships they had expected and hoped for. Food had been dispatched from France and Britain, but it was in [[Brindisi]], on the other side of the Adriatic, and the Italians had not allocated more than a few small vessels to transport it on to the Serbs.<ref name=\":8\" /> Some supplies had come ashore in Durr\u00ebs, so the columns of troops and refugees had no choice but to set off on further marches south.<ref name=\":8\" /> Eventually, a decision was made to evacuate the Serbian Army, and its accompanying civilians, to the French-occupied [[Corfu|Greek island of Corfu]] and as far as [[Bizerte|Bizerta]] in [[French protectorate of Tunisia|French Tunisia]].<ref>Thomas, Babac 2012, p. 95</ref> This decision, made primarily by the French and British, did not involve any discussions with the Greek authorities.<ref name=\":8\" /> The French sent their navy and the evacuation started on 15 January; the embarkation was made from three ports, [[Sh\u00ebngjin|San Giovanni di Medua]], [[Durr\u00ebs]] and [[Vlor\u00eb|Valona]].<ref>Gordon-Smith 1920, p. 195</ref>  \n\nOn 14 January the Serbian government, ministers, and the members of the diplomatic corps boarded an Italian ship, the ''Citta di Bari'', for [[Brindisi]].<ref name=\":7\" /> On 6 February the Serbian supreme command and Regent Alexander were evacuated to Corfu, where around 120,000 evacuees had arrived by 15 February, and around 135,000 ten days later. Up to 10,000 evacuees were taken to Bizerta around the same time. The [[Italian Navy|Italians]] took over the majority of Habsburg prisoners, and transferred them to the uninhabited island of [[Asinara]] (off the coast of [[Sardinia]]).<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nMost of the Serb troops had been evacuated by 19 February. The cavalry division was last to embark on 5 April 1916, which marked the end of the operation.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Th\u00e9ophile Alexandre Steinlen 25 Juin 1916 - Journ\u00e9e Serbe.jpg|thumb|upright|Serbia Day, organized in [[Paris]] for the benefit of the Serbian Relief Fund on 25 June 1916 to coincide with the approximate date of the first [[Battle of Kosovo]]. Poster by [[Th\u00e9ophile Steinlen|Theophile Alexandre Steinlen]]]]\nAccording to the official statistics from 1919, 77,455 Serbian soldiers died, while 77,278 went missing. The worst fate befell the Southern Column, where approximately 43,000 young boys that would have become conscripts in 1916 had been taken by the Army to join the retreat; within a month approximately 36,000 of them died.<ref>Reader's Digest, 2000</ref>\n\nOf the estimated 220,000 civilian refugees who had set off for the Adriatic coast from [[Kosovo region|Kosovo]], only about 60,000 survived. Those who survived were so weak that thousands of them died from sheer exhaustion in the weeks after their rescue. Because the rock composition of the island made it hard to dig graves, those who died on the journey were buried at sea. Bodies were lowered from French ships into the depths of the [[Ionian Sea]], near the Greek island of [[Vido]]; more than 5,000 Serbs are believed to have been buried this way. The sea around Vido is known as \"The Blue Graveyard\" (''[[Plava Grobnica]]'')\"<ref>Askew 1916, p. 360</ref><br>Field Marshal Putnik traveled to France for medical treatment, where he died the following year.<ref>Buttar 2015, p.</ref> The Serbian Army was subsequently redeployed after Greece entered the war on the Allied side; some six Serbian infantry divisions and one cavalry division would eventually return to serve, playing a key role in the breakthrough of [[Macedonian front|the Macedonian Front]] in September 1917, and the [[Liberation of Serbia, Albania and Montenegro (1918)|liberation]] of their homeland a year later.<ref>Hart 2015, p 189</ref>\n\nThe retreat of the Serbian Army across Albania is considered by Serbs to be one of the greatest tragedies in their nation's history.<ref name=\":5\">Gordon-Smith 1920, p.1</ref>\n\n==Images==\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"140\" caption=\"The Great Retreat\">\nFile:Serbian cavalry crossing the Black Drin River during the retreat to the Adriatic Sea Coast 1915.jpg|Serbian cavalry crossing the Black Drin\nFile:Field Marshal Radomir Putnik, the Chief of the General Staff of the Serbian Army, being carried by bearers across the bridge over the Drin River 1915.jpg|Field Marshal Radomir Putnik being carried by bearers\nFile:Serbian artillery during the retreat to the Adriatic Sea coast 1915.jpg|Serbian artillery during the retreat\nFile:Serbian troops and refugees during the retreat to the Adriatic Sea coast 1915.jpg|Serbian troops and refugees during the retreat\nFile:The Column of the First Serbian-English Field Hospital.tif|The Column of the First Serbian-English Field Hospital\nFile:Serbiancolumnretreat1915.jpg|A column of Serbian soldiers\nFile:Ukrcavanje 1916.jpg|Evacuation of the Serbian army\nFile:Serbian troops in Corfu 1916.jpg|Serbian troops in Corfu, Feb 1916\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Albanian Commemorative Medal|Commemorative Medal of the Great Serbian Retreat]]\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/title/gde-cveta-limun-zut/oclc/958005221&referer=brief_results Gde Cveta Limun \u017dut, (2006)]. A documentary film about the Serbian army's retreat.\n*[[King Peter of Serbia]], (2018). A feature film starring [[Lazar Ristovski]].\n*[[Kre\u0107e se la\u0111a francuska]], A World War I song composed by [[Branislav Milosavljevi\u0107]] in Corfu.\n*[[Tamo Daleko]], A World War I song composed in Corfu.\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|15em}}\n\n=== Books ===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Alice Askew|author2=Claude Arthur Cary Askew|title=The Stricken Land: Serbia as We Saw it|url=https://archive.org/details/strickenlandserb00aske|page=[https://archive.org/details/strickenlandserb00aske/page/360 360]|year=1916|publisher=E. Nash}}\n*{{cite book|author=Prit Buttar|title=Germany Ascendant: The Eastern Front 1915|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tp-HCwAAQBAJ|date=20 August 2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4728-1355-8}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Marie-Janine Calic|title=A History of Yugoslavia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F16cswEACAAJ|year=2019|publisher=Purdue University Press|isbn=978-1-55753-838-3}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Dinardo|first=Richard L.|title=Invasion: The Conquest of Serbia, 1915|year=2015|location=Santa Bar