6e\u60f3\u3044}}  \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Kyomu\"|\u865a\u7121}}  \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Koe\"|\u58f0}}   \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Yuganda Kokoro -Kunou-\"|\u6b6a\u3093\u3060\u5fc3-\u82e6\u60a9-}} \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Yuuki\"|\u52c7\u6c17}}  \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Jikuuryuu no Tatakai\"|\u6642\u7a7a\u6d41\u306e\u6226\u3044}}  \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Ankoku no Nodosu\"|\u6697\u9ed2\u306e\u30ce\u30c9\u30b9}}  \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Heroic Age -Kagayaku no Hoshi Tatsu Toki-\"|\u30d2\u30ed\u30a4\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30a8\u30a4\u30b8-\u8f1d\u304d\u306e\u661f\u7acb\u3064\u3068\u304d-}}  \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Yuganda Kokoro -Kyoufu-\"|\u6b6a\u3093\u3060\u5fc3-\u6050\u6016-}} \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Omowaku\"|\u601d\u60d1}}  \t\n#{{nihongo|\"Chitsujo\"|\u79e9\u5e8f}}\t\n#{{nihongo|\"Heroic Age -Kikan-\"|\u30d2\u30ed\u30a4\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30a8\u30a4\u30b8-\u5e30\u9084-}}\t\n{{col-2}}\n;Disc 2\nThe second disc describes some events surrounding Iolaous, outside the ''Heroic Age'' story.<ref name=\"Music section\"/> The disc also features a bonus track, \"Flowery\", with vocals by Dhianeila's voice actress, Yui Ishikawa.\n\n;Performance:\n*[[Takashi Kond\u014d]] as Iolaous\n*[[Yukari Tamura]] as Tail\n*[[Rie Kugimiya]] as Mail\n*[[Kaori Shimizu]] as Aneasha\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tv-tokyo.co.jp/anime/heroic_age/ TV Tokyo Official Site] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070406191717/http://www.xebec-inc.co.jp/anime/heroicage/ XEBEC Official Site] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.starchild.co.jp/special/heroicage/ Starchild Site] {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{ann|anime|7627|Heroic Age}}\n*[http://funimation.com/heroicage/ The Official Heroic Age Anime Website From FUNimation]\n\n{{Xebec}}\n\n[[Category:Adventure anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Anime with original screenplays]]\n[[Category:Funimation]]\n[[Category:Kodansha manga]]\n[[Category:IG Port franchises]]\n[[Category:Mecha anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Seinen manga]]\n[[Category:Xebec (studio)]]\n[[Category:Space opera anime and manga]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDVDs:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1-26 \u2192 1\u201326", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heroic_Age_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Goth (novel)", "text_new": "{{fanpov|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = Goth\n| image           = GothManga.jpg\n| caption         = Front cover of the manga\n| ja_kanji        = \u30b4\u30b9\n| ja_romaji       = Gosu\n| genre           = [[Horror fiction|Horror]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.viz.com/goth |title=The Official Website for Goth |publisher=Viz Media |accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref><!-- Note: Use and cite reliable sources to identify genre/s, not personal interpretation. Please don't include more than three genres (per [[MOS:A&M]]). -->\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = novel\n| author          = [[Otsuichi]]\n| publisher       = [[Kadokawa Shoten]]\n| publisher_en    = {{English manga publisher|NA=[[Tokyopop]]}}\n| demographic     = \n| imprint         = \n| published       = May 30, 2003\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Otsu-ichi]]\n| illustrator     = [[Kendi Oiwa]]\n| publisher       = [[Kadokawa Comics]]\n| publisher_en    = {{English manga publisher|NA=[[Tokyopop]]}}\n| demographic     = ''[[Seinen manga|Seinen]]''\n| published       = 2004\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Other\n| title           = Feature films\n| content         = \n* ''[[Goth (2008 film)|Goth]]''\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''GOTH'''''|\u30b4\u30b9|Gosu}} is a Japanese horror novel written by [[Otsuichi]] about two high school students fascinated by murder. The novel won the [[Honkaku Mystery Award]] in 2003.<ref>[http://honkaku.com/english.html The Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan]</ref> It was adapted into a manga by [[Kendi Oiwa]]. Both were published in Japan by [[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]], and were published in English by [[Tokyopop]] in October and September, 2008. In 2008, the novel was adapted into a [[Goth (2008 film)|film of the same title]] directed by [[Gen Takahashi]]. The manga and novel was rereleased in North America by VIZ Media in  August 2015.\n\n==Plot==\nThe novel contains a series of six short stories about two high school students: beginning with a boy (Kamiyama) who remains unnamed until late in the story,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jaffari|first=Elizabeth|date=|title=Monstrous Ambiguity and Desire in Otsuichi\u2019s Goth|url=http://csusm-dspace.calstate.edu/handle/10211.3/194902|journal=LTWR|publisher=California State University San Marcos|volume=|pages=13|via=}}</ref> and a girl named Yoru Morino. Both share a similar interest in gruesome murders.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jaffari|first=Elizabeth|date=|title=Monstrous Ambiguity and Desire in Otsuichi\u2019s Goth|url=http://csusm-dspace.calstate.edu/handle/10211.3/194902|journal=LTWR|publisher=California State University San Marcos|volume=|pages=1-2|via=}}</ref> While the stories were originally published in a single hardcover edition, they were later published in two bunko volumes. Tokyopop's release follows the original one-volume format. The manga adaptation, by Kendi Oiwa, eliminates the Dog storyline, and combines Voice and Twins, with Morino taking Natsumi's role in the final story.\n\n* '''{{nihongo|Goth|\u6697\u9ed2\u7cfb|Ankokukei|Dark Type}}''' - Morino finds a diary written by a serial killer. It describes a third victim that has yet to be discovered, so she and the narrator go to look at it. Morino then begins dressing like the third victim, and a few days later, sends a text message to the narrator, which reads only, \"Help.\"\n* '''{{nihongo|Wristcut|\u30ea\u30b9\u30c8\u30ab\u30c3\u30c8\u4e8b\u4ef6|Risutokatto Jiken|The Wristcut Incident}}''' - Flashback to before Morino and the narrator were friends. After finding a doll with no hands in the science lab garbage can, the narrator breaks into the science teacher's house, convinced he has been the one cutting hands off people of all ages in the city. He then steals the teacher's hand collection, and plants evidence to suggest Morino was the one who stole them - because he wants Morino's hand, and the scar from when she cut her wrist.\n* '''{{nihongo|Dog|\u72ac|Inu|Dog}}''' - The narrator investigates a series of dog kidnappings after his sister discovers a pit filled with their bodies. A young girl and her pet dog have been plotting to defend themselves against her mother's abusive boyfriend.\n* '''{{nihongo|Twins|\u8a18\u61b6|Kioku|Memories}}''' - Morino has been having trouble sleeping, and is looking for a rope to put around her neck - the right rope will help her sleep. At the narrator's urging, she tells the story of how she and her twin sister, Y\u016b, often pretended to be dead...until Y\u016b accidentally hanged herself.\n* '''{{nihongo|Grave|\u571f|Tsuchi|Soil}}''' - Saeki spends all his free time gardening, digging holes to try to control his obsession with burying people alive. He's already given in once, and killed a young neighbor boy, drowning him in his coffin. Now he's snatched a high school girl off the street - according to her ID, her name is Yoru Morino.\n* '''{{nihongo|Voice|\u58f0|Koe|Voice}}''' - Natsumi's older sister was recently found chopped to pieces in an abandoned hospital. A few weeks later, a mysterious high school boy gives Natsumi a tape - a message from her sister, recorded just before she was murdered. If she wants the rest, she will have to come to the hospital, and allow him to murder her.\n\n==Characters==\n;Boku: The narrator. A handsome high school student obsessed with death. Said his passions are to \"haunt crime scenes to look for details\" and to \"stand where a body had been not long ago\". Yearns to watch Morino's death.\n;Yoru Morino: A beautiful high school student obsessed with death. Tends to keep to herself and not talk to anyone. Befriends the narrator after an incident involving Mr. Shinohara. Has a glaring white scar on her wrist.\n;Mr. Shinohara:Morino's science teacher. Has an obsession with hands. \n\n==== The Cafe Manager ====\n\n:A manager at Morino's favorite cafe. He is never named.\n;Mr. Saeki:A man who lives near Morino. He's obsessed with burying people alive.\n;Y\u016b Morino:Yoru's twin sister.\n;Natsumi Kitazawa:Her older sister was recently murdered, and her world has fallen apart. When a mysterious boy approaches her with a tape of her sister's final words, she can't stop herself from listening.\n;Itsuki Kamiyama:A friend of Natsumi's from junior high, he is a student at the same school as the boy who gave her the tape. While he seems outgoing and friendly, at the end of the novel he is revealed to be the previously unnamed narrator.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Novel===\nWritten by [[Otsuichi]], '''''GOTH''''' was published in Japan by [[Kadokawa Shoten]] ({{ISBN|4-04-873390-7}}) in 2002, and later released in a two volume [[bunkobon]] version named {{nihongo|'''''Goth Yoru no Sh\u014d'''''|GOTH \u591c\u306e\u7ae0|}} ({{ISBN|4-04-425304-8}}) and {{nihongo|'''''Goth Boku no Sh\u014d'''''|GOTH \u50d5\u306e\u7ae0|}} ({{ISBN|4-04-425305-6}}).\n\n[[Tokyopop]] licensed the novel for an English-language release in North America,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-03-14/TOKYOPOP-to-release-otsu-ichi-goth-novel-manga|title=Tokyopop to release Otsu-Ichi's Goth Novel, Manga|date=14 March 2008|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=29 December 2009}}</ref> and published it on October 7, 2008.<ref name=\"Tokyopop catalog\"/>\n\n===Manga===\n\nThe manga adaption was licensed by Tokyopop and published on September 9, 2008.<ref name=\"Tokyopop catalog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyopop.com/manga/book_catalog/browse?alphabet=g-i&hide_adult=Y&p=6 |title=Manga+Comics: Book Catalog |publisher=[[Tokyopop]] |accessdate=29 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823121317/http://www.tokyopop.com/manga/book_catalog/browse?alphabet=g-i&hide_adult=Y&p=6 |archivedate=23 August 2009 }}</ref> \nIt is also licensed in Italy by [[Planet Manga]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paninicomics.it/web/guest/search_product?search=Goth|title=Goth|publisher=[[Planet Manga]]|language=Italian|accessdate=29 December 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Xssvhsx?url=http://www.paninicomics.it/web/guest/search_product?search=Goth|archivedate=19 June 2012}}</ref> in France by [[Pika \u00c9dition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pika.fr/new/node/1210 |title=Goth |publisher=[[Pika \u00c9dition]] |language=French |accessdate=29 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311220939/http://www.pika.fr/new/node/1210 |archivedate=11 March 2010 }}</ref> in Germany by [[Egmont Manga & Anime]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manganet.de/index.php/cat/c340_goth.html?view=reihenintro |title=Goth |publisher=[[Egmont Manga & Anime]] |language=German |accessdate=29 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227131821/http://www.manganet.de/index.php/cat/c340_goth.html?view=reihenintro |archivedate=27 December 2009 }}</ref>  and in Russia by [[Comics Factory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comics-factory.ru/?page_id=5|title=Comic books index|publisher=[[Comics Factory]]|language=Russian|accessdate=5 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nBased upon the novel by Otsuichi, ''[[Goth (2008 film)|Goth]]'' is about two morbid high school students who share a fascination with murder. Kamiyama ([[Kanata Hong\u014d]]) is an outwardly, friendly and popular boy who hides his potentially sociopathic nature with a carefree, happy attitude. Loner Morino ([[Rin Takanashi]]), on the other hand, does little to hide her strange nature; she never smiles, does not interact with her classmates, and wears a long-sleeved, black school uniform even during the middle of summer. While these two seem to share little in common and do not interact with each other in front of their peers, their shared interest in death and murder has turned them into an unusual duo. Initially happy to exchange books on morbid subjects, a series of recent murders spark their interest and they begin investigating the killer. This serial killer has a fondness for cheerful young women and, after severing their left hand as a trophy, displays their dead bodies in public locations to be discovered. After Morino discovers the killer's notebook in a local caf\u00e9, the two use it to see the corpses for themselves before discovery and attempt to discern his identity. {{Why|reason=It is unclear why a plot summary of the movie is included here. More relevant to the novel, might be details such as who directed the movie, or when it was released (as consistent with the 'manga' subsection) |date=February 2020}}\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{ann|novel|17343|Goth}}\n\n[[Category:2003 manga]]\n[[Category:Horror anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Japanese horror novels]]\n[[Category:Seinen manga]]\n", "text_old": "{{fanpov|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = Goth\n| image           = GothManga.jpg\n| caption         = Front cover of the manga\n| ja_kanji        = \u30b4\u30b9\n| ja_romaji       = Gosu\n| genre           = [[Horror fiction|Horror]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.viz.com/goth |title=The Official Website for Goth |publisher=Viz Media |accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref><!-- Note: Use and cite reliable sources to identify genre/s, not personal interpretation. Please don't include more than three genres (per [[MOS:A&M]]). -->\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = novel\n| author          = [[Otsuichi]]\n| publisher       = [[Kadokawa Shoten]]\n| publisher_en    = {{English manga publisher|NA=[[Tokyopop]]}}\n| demographic     = \n| imprint         = \n| published       = May 30, 2003\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Otsu-ichi]]\n| illustrator     = [[Kendi Oiwa]]\n| publisher       = [[Kadokawa Comics]]\n| publisher_en    = {{English manga publisher|NA=[[Tokyopop]]}}\n| demographic     = ''[[Seinen manga|Seinen]]''\n| published       = 2004\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Other\n| title           = Feature films\n| content         = \n* ''[[Goth (2008 film)|Goth]]''\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''GOTH'''''|\u30b4\u30b9|Gosu}} is a Japanese horror novel written by [[Otsuichi]] about two high school students fascinated by murder. The novel won the [[Honkaku Mystery Award]] in 2003.<ref>[http://honkaku.com/english.html The Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan]</ref> It was adapted into a manga by [[Kendi Oiwa]]. Both were published in Japan by [[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]], and were published in English by [[Tokyopop]] in October and September, 2008. In 2008, the novel was adapted into a [[Goth (2008 film)|film of the same title]] directed by [[Gen Takahashi]]. The manga and novel was rereleased in North America by VIZ Media in  August 2015.\n\n==Plot==\nThe novel contains a series of six short stories about two high school students: beginning with a boy (Kamiyama) who remains unnamed until late in the story,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jaffari|first=Elizabeth|date=|title=Monstrous Ambiguity and Desire in Otsuichi\u2019s Goth|url=http://csusm-dspace.calstate.edu/handle/10211.3/194902|journal=LTWR|publisher=California State University San Marcos|volume=|pages=13|via=}}</ref> and a girl named Yoru Morino. Both share a similar interest in gruesome murders.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jaffari|first=Elizabeth|date=|title=Monstrous Ambiguity and Desire in Otsuichi\u2019s Goth|url=http://csusm-dspace.calstate.edu/handle/10211.3/194902|journal=LTWR|publisher=California State University San Marcos|volume=|pages=1-2|via=}}</ref> While the stories were originally published in a single hardcover edition, they were later published in two bunko volumes. Tokyopop's release follows the original one-volume format. The manga adaptation, by Kendi Oiwa, eliminates the Dog storyline, and combines Voice and Twins, with Morino taking Natsumi's role in the final story.\n\n* '''{{nihongo|Goth|\u6697\u9ed2\u7cfb|Ankokukei|Dark Type}}''' - Morino finds a diary written by a serial killer. It describes a third victim that has yet to be discovered, so she and the narrator go to look at it. Morino then begins dressing like the third victim, and a few days later, sends a text message to the narrator, which reads only, \"Help.\"\n* '''{{nihongo|Wristcut|\u30ea\u30b9\u30c8\u30ab\u30c3\u30c8\u4e8b\u4ef6|Risutokatto Jiken|The Wristcut Incident}}''' - Flashback to before Morino and the narrator were friends. After finding a doll with no hands in the science lab garbage can, the narrator breaks into the science teacher's house, convinced he has been the one cutting hands off people of all ages in the city. He then steals the teacher's hand collection, and plants evidence to suggest Morino was the one who stole them - because he wants Morino's hand, and the scar from when she cut her wrist.\n* '''{{nihongo|Dog|\u72ac|Inu|Dog}}''' - The narrator investigates a series of dog kidnappings after his sister discovers a pit filled with their bodies. A young girl and her pet dog have been plotting to defend themselves against her mother's abusive boyfriend.\n* '''{{nihongo|Twins|\u8a18\u61b6|Kioku|Memories}}''' - Morino has been having trouble sleeping, and is looking for a rope to put around her neck - the right rope will help her sleep. At the narrator's urging, she tells the story of how she and her twin sister, Y\u016b, often pretended to be dead...until Y\u016b accidentally hanged herself.\n* '''{{nihongo|Grave|\u571f|Tsuchi|Soil}}''' - Saeki spends all his free time gardening, digging holes to try to control his obsession with burying people alive. He's already given in once, and killed a young neighbor boy, drowning him in his coffin. Now he's snatched a high school girl off the street - according to her ID, her name is Yoru Morino.\n* '''{{nihongo|Voice|\u58f0|Koe|Voice}}''' - Natsumi's older sister was recently found chopped to pieces in an abandoned hospital. A few weeks later, a mysterious high school boy gives Natsumi a tape - a message from her sister, recorded just before she was murdered. If she wants the rest, she will have to come to the hospital, and allow him to murder her.\n\n==Characters==\n;Boku: The narrator. A handsome high school student obsessed with death. Said his passions are to \"haunt crime scenes to look for details\" and to \"stand where a body had been not long ago\". Yearns to watch Morino's death.\n;Yoru Morino: A beautiful high school student obsessed with death. Tends to keep to herself and not talk to anyone. Befriends the narrator after an incident involving Mr. Shinohara. Has a glaring white scar on her wrist.\n;Mr. Shinohara:Morino's science teacher. Has an obsession with hands. \n\n==== The Cafe Manager ====\n\n:A manager at Morino's favorite cafe. He is never named.\n;Mr. Saeki:A man who lives near Morino. He's obsessed with burying people alive.\n;Y\u016b Morino:Yoru's twin sister.\n;Natsumi Kitazawa:Her older sister was recently murdered, and her world has fallen apart. When a mysterious boy approaches her with a tape of her sister's final words, she can't stop herself from listening.\n;Itsuki Kamiyama:A friend of Natsumi's from junior high, he is a student at the same school as the boy who gave her the tape. While he seems outgoing and friendly, at the end of the novel he is revealed to be the previously unnamed narrator.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Novel===\nWritten by [[Otsuichi]], '''''GOTH''''' was published in Japan by [[Kadokawa Shoten]] ({{ISBN|4-04-873390-7}}) in 2002, and later released in a two volume [[bunkobon]] version named {{nihongo|'''''Goth Yoru no Sh\u014d'''''|GOTH \u591c\u306e\u7ae0|}} ({{ISBN|4-04-425304-8}}) and {{nihongo|'''''Goth Boku no Sh\u014d'''''|GOTH \u50d5\u306e\u7ae0|}} ({{ISBN|4-04-425305-6}}).\n\n[[Tokyopop]] licensed the novel for an English-language release in North America,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-03-14/TOKYOPOP-to-release-otsu-ichi-goth-novel-manga|title=Tokyopop to release Otsu-Ichi's Goth Novel, Manga|date=14 March 2008|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=29 December 2009}}</ref> and published it on October 7, 2008.<ref name=\"Tokyopop catalog\"/>\n\n===Manga===\n\nThe manga adaption was licensed by Tokyopop and published on September 9, 2008.<ref name=\"Tokyopop catalog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyopop.com/manga/book_catalog/browse?alphabet=g-i&hide_adult=Y&p=6 |title=Manga+Comics: Book Catalog |publisher=[[Tokyopop]] |accessdate=29 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823121317/http://www.tokyopop.com/manga/book_catalog/browse?alphabet=g-i&hide_adult=Y&p=6 |archivedate=23 August 2009 }}</ref> \nIt is also licensed in Italy by [[Planet Manga]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paninicomics.it/web/guest/search_product?search=Goth|title=Goth|publisher=[[Planet Manga]]|language=Italian|accessdate=29 December 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Xssvhsx?url=http://www.paninicomics.it/web/guest/search_product?search=Goth|archivedate=19 June 2012}}</ref> in France by [[Pika \u00c9dition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pika.fr/new/node/1210 |title=Goth |publisher=[[Pika \u00c9dition]] |language=French |accessdate=29 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311220939/http://www.pika.fr/new/node/1210 |archivedate=11 March 2010 }}</ref> in Germany by [[Egmont Manga & Anime]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manganet.de/index.php/cat/c340_goth.html?view=reihenintro |title=Goth |publisher=[[Egmont Manga & Anime]] |language=German |accessdate=29 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227131821/http://www.manganet.de/index.php/cat/c340_goth.html?view=reihenintro |archivedate=27 December 2009 }}</ref>  and in Russia by [[Comics Factory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comics-factory.ru/?page_id=5|title=Comic books index|publisher=[[Comics Factory]]|language=Russian|accessdate=5 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nBased upon the novel by Otsuichi, ''[[Goth (2008 film)|Goth]]'' is about two morbid high school students who share a fascination with murder. Kamiyama ([[Kanata Hong\u014d]]) is an outwardly, friendly and popular boy who hides his potentially sociopathic nature with a carefree, happy attitude. Loner Morino ([[Rin Takanashi]]), on the other hand, does little to hide her strange nature; she never smiles, does not interact with her classmates, and wears a long-sleeved, black school uniform even during the middle of summer. While these two seem to share little in common and do not interact with each other in front of their peers, their shared interest in death and murder has turned them into an unusual duo. Initially happy to exchange books on morbid subjects, a series of recent murders spark their interest and they begin investigating the killer. This serial killer has a fondness for cheerful young women and, after severing their left hand as a trophy, displays their dead bodies in public locations to be discovered. After Morino discovers the killer\u2019s notebook in a local caf\u00e9, the two use it to see the corpses for themselves before discovery and attempt to discern his identity. {{Why|reason=It is unclear why a plot summary of the movie is included here. More relevant to the novel, might be details such as who directed the movie, or when it was released (as consistent with the 'manga' subsection) |date=February 2020}}\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{ann|novel|17343|Goth}}\n\n[[Category:2003 manga]]\n[[Category:Horror anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Japanese horror novels]]\n[[Category:Seinen manga]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilm:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goth_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Gansu Wind Farm", "text_new": "{{Infobox power station \n| name                   = Gansu Wind Farm\n| name_official          = \n| image                  = \n| image_size             = \n| image_caption          = \n| image_alt              = \n| location_map           = China\n| location_map_size      = \n| location_map_caption   = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|40|12|N|96|54|E|region:CN_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}<br/>{{coord |40.2|N|96.9|E}}<br/>{{coord |40.6|N|96.9|E}}<br/>{{coord |40.23|N|97.13|E}}\n| country                = [[People's Republic of China|China]]\n| location               = [[Gansu]]\n| status                 = o\n| construction_began     = 2009\n| commissioned           = \n| decommissioned         = \n| cost                   = \n| owner                  = multiple\n| operator               = \n| ps_units_manu_model    = \n| wind_hub_height        = \n| wind_rotor_diameter    = \n| wind_rated_speed       = \n| wind_farm_type         = Onshore\n| wind_site_elevation    = \n| wind_site_usage        = \n| wind_site_area         = \n| wind_offshore_depth    = \n| wind_offshore_distance = \n| ps_electrical_capacity = 7,965 MW<br/>Planned: 20,000 MW\n| ps_electrical_cap_fac  = \n| ps_annual_generation   = \n| website                = \n| extra                  = \n}}\n\nThe '''Gansu Wind Farm Project''' or '''Jiuquan Wind Power Base''' is a group of large [[wind farm]]s under construction in western [[Gansu province]] in [[China]].  The Gansu Wind Farm Project is located in desert areas near the city of [[Jiuquan]] in two localities of [[Guazhou County]] and also near [[Yumen City]], in the northwest province of [[Gansu]], which has an abundance of wind resources.<ref name=\"CD-2010.11.04\" />\nThe complex is operating at below 40% utilization of the current 8 GW with a planned capacity of 20 GW.<ref name=nyt/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://interestingengineering.com/the-11-biggest-wind-farms-and-wind-power-constructions-that-reduce-carbon-footprint|title=The 11 Biggest Wind Farms and Wind Power Constructions That Reduce Carbon Footprint|last=Vyas|first=Kashyap|date=15 February 2018|work=Interesting Engineering|access-date=2018-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221182756/https://interestingengineering.com/the-11-biggest-wind-farms-and-wind-power-constructions-that-reduce-carbon-footprint|archive-date=21 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nThe project is one of six national [[wind power]] megaprojects approved by the [[Government of the People's Republic of China|Chinese government]].<ref name=\"CD-2010.11.04\" /> It is expected to grow to 20,000 [[megawatts]] by 2020, at an estimated cost of 120 billion Chinese yuan ($17.5 billion). The project is being built by more than 20 developers in two localities in [[Guazhou County]] and also near [[Yumen City]].<ref name=reu>[https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5771IP20090808 China Starts Building First 10-GW Mega Wind Farm] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229230350/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5771IP20090808 |date=2010-12-29 }}, ''[[Reuters]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windpowermonthly.com/news/1016805/Chinas-Jiuquan-wind-farm-speeds-construction/|title=China's Jiuquan wind farm speeds up construction|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301051721/http://www.windpowermonthly.com/news/1016805/Chinas-Jiuquan-wind-farm-speeds-construction/|archive-date=1 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{wide image|Gansu.Guazhou.windfarm.croped.jpg|1000px|A small part of the huge Guazhou wind turbine farm}}\n\n== Construction phases ==\n[[File:Wind Farm In Gansu PRC.JPG|thumb|A wind turbine in the wind farm]]\n[[File:Guazhou.champs \u00e9oliennes.2.jpg|thumb|Gansu Wind Farm]]\nThe project is divided into multiple phases. The first 3,800 MW phase consisted of eighteen 200 MW wind farms and two 100 MW wind farms. The second 8,000 MW phase consists of forty 200 MW wind farms. The planned capacity is 5,160 MW by 2010, 12,710 MW by 2015 and 20,000 MW in 2020.<ref name=reu />\n\nIn 2008, construction began on a 750 kV AC power line to carry electricity from the wind farm,<ref>Peter Fairley. [http://www.technologyreview.com/energy/23460/page2/ China's Potent Wind Potential] ''[[Technology Review]]'', September 14, 2009.</ref> and construction of the wind farms themselves started in August 2009.<ref name=reu /> Power in 2012 was being purchased for 0.54 yuan per kWh, compared with electricity from coal fired powerplants at 0.3 yuan per kWh.<ref name=\"Guardian-2012.03.19\">Watts, Jonathan & Huang, Cecily. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/mar/19/china-windfarms-renewable-energy Winds Of Change Blow Through China As Spending On Renewable Energy Soars] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203225721/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/mar/19/china-windfarms-renewable-energy |date=2016-12-03 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', March 19, 2012, revised on March 20, 2012. Retrieved January 4, 2012.</ref> Since operations began, some 6.26 billion kWh has been generated as of October 31, 2011 with 5.96 billion kWh of that produced in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2011/11/02/5902457.htm|title=Wind power generation from Jiuquan base hits 6.26 bln kwh by end-Oct.|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528182208/http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2011/11/02/5902457.htm|archive-date=28 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010 officials announced the completion of the project's first phase, involving the installation of over 3,500 wind turbines with an installed capacity of approximately 5,160 MW according to Wang Jianxin, director of the Jiuquan Development and Reform Commission.<ref name=\"CD-2010.11.04\">[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/bizchina/2010-11/04/content_11502951.htm Xinhua: Jiuquan Wind Power Base Completes First Stage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107133402/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/bizchina/2010-11/04/content_11502951.htm |date=2010-11-07 }}, ''[[Xinhua News Agency]]'', November 4, 2010. Retrieved from ChinaDaily.com.cn website January 3, 2013.</ref> Total installed capacity rose to approximately 6,000 MW in March 2012\u2014roughly equivalent to the United Kingdom's entire wind power capacity at that time.\n\n==Coordinated control centre==\nOn March 1, 2012, a \"wind power coordinated control system\" was implemented to adjust the output of the 18 wind farms of the Gansu Wind Farm Project, which total 10&nbsp;GW, to meet the needs of the transmission grid, which is limited to 1.5&nbsp;GW. This permitted the production of 1&nbsp;GWh more per day than previously, and greatly improves the system's stability.<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeccomposites.com/news/composites-news/china-northwest-grid-wind-electricity-coordinated-control-system|title=China northwest grid wind electricity coordinated control system|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528181128/http://www.jeccomposites.com/news/composites-news/china-northwest-grid-wind-electricity-coordinated-control-system|archive-date=28 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCurtailment of wind turbine operations is a first order method for dealing with the [[intermittent power source|intermittency]] of wind, but normally loses available output when the power grid's transmission capacity has been reached. Other methods involve either added local industrial usage or added local storage capacity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy10osti/47187.pdf |title=The Role Of Energy Storage With Renewable Electricity Generation |access-date=2012-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916224824/http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy10osti/47187.pdf |archive-date=2012-09-16 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ewp.rpi.edu/hartford/users/papers/engr/ernesto/farrew2/Project/research/1D543506d01.pdf |title=Management of variable electricity loads in wind e Hydrogen systems: The case of a Spanish wind farm |access-date=2012-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072531/http://www.ewp.rpi.edu/hartford/users/papers/engr/ernesto/farrew2/Project/research/1D543506d01.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Demand and utilization==\nWith local-government favoritism toward coal and inadequate long-distance transmission capacity, Gansu \"now has some of the highest rates of underutilization in the wind sector in China\". [[National Development and Reform Commission#National Energy Administration|National Energy Administration]] statistics showed 39 percent of wind capacity in 2015 in Jiuquan was wasted.<ref name=nyt/>\n\nAs of 2017, Gansu is far from full capacity and the wind farm is producing less than half of its full potential. The two main reasons why this is happening is that Gansu is located far from the major Chinese cities and that there is a lack of demand for wind energy in China.<ref name=nyt>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/15/world/asia/china-gansu-wind-farm.html|title=It Can Power a Small Nation. But This Wind Farm in China Is Mostly Idle.|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Javier C.|date=2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202152938/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/15/world/asia/china-gansu-wind-farm.html|archive-date=2017-12-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Gansu wind farm sits along the [[Gobi desert]] where there are extremely high winds. However, this location is about a thousand miles from China's high density port cities that would serve as the biggest consumer of this energy.<ref name=nyt/>\nThere is a lack of enough infrastructure and transmission lines that would allow the energy to flow into the cities.\nThere is still also little demand for wind power in China compared to coal. Although China's central government is actively trying to reduce its emissions and build its clean energy sector, the local governments still push coal on their local industries because it creates more economic output and because the coal is mined locally, which helps local coal companies.<ref name=nyt/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|China|Weather|Renewable energy|Energy}}}}\n* [[List of largest power stations]]\n* [[List of onshore wind farms]]\n* [[List of power stations in China]]\n* [[Megaproject]]\n* [[Wind power in China]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wind power in China}}\n\n[[Category:Wind farms in China]]\n[[Category:Engineering projects]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox power station \n| name                   = Gansu Wind Farm\n| name_official          = \n| image                  = \n| image_size             = \n| image_caption          = \n| image_alt              = \n| location_map           = China\n| location_map_size      = \n| location_map_caption   = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|40|12|N|96|54|E|region:CN_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}<br/>{{coord |40.2|N|96.9|E}}<br/>{{coord |40.6|N|96.9|E}}<br/>{{coord |40.23|N|97.13|E}}\n| country                = [[People's Republic of China|China]]\n| location               = [[Gansu]]\n| status                 = o\n| construction_began     = 2009\n| commissioned           = \n| decommissioned         = \n| cost                   = \n| owner                  = multiple\n| operator               = \n| ps_units_manu_model    = \n| wind_hub_height        = \n| wind_rotor_diameter    = \n| wind_rated_speed       = \n| wind_farm_type         = Onshore\n| wind_site_elevation    = \n| wind_site_usage        = \n| wind_site_area         = \n| wind_offshore_depth    = \n| wind_offshore_distance = \n| ps_electrical_capacity = 7,965 MW<br/>Planned: 20,000 MW\n| ps_electrical_cap_fac  = \n| ps_annual_generation   = \n| website                = \n| extra                  = \n}}\n\nThe '''Gansu Wind Farm Project''' or '''Jiuquan Wind Power Base''' is a group of large [[wind farm]]s under construction in western [[Gansu province]] in [[China]].  The Gansu Wind Farm Project is located in desert areas near the city of [[Jiuquan]] in two localities of [[Guazhou County]] and also near [[Yumen City]], in the northwest province of [[Gansu]], which has an abundance of wind resources.<ref name=\"CD-2010.11.04\" />\nThe complex is operating at below 40% utilization of the current 8 GW with a planned capacity of 20 GW.<ref name=nyt/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://interestingengineering.com/the-11-biggest-wind-farms-and-wind-power-constructions-that-reduce-carbon-footprint|title=The 11 Biggest Wind Farms and Wind Power Constructions That Reduce Carbon Footprint|last=Vyas|first=Kashyap|date=15 February 2018|work=Interesting Engineering|access-date=2018-12-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221182756/https://interestingengineering.com/the-11-biggest-wind-farms-and-wind-power-constructions-that-reduce-carbon-footprint|archive-date=21 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nThe project is one of six national [[wind power]] megaprojects approved by the [[Government of the People's Republic of China|Chinese government]].<ref name=\"CD-2010.11.04\" /> It is expected to grow to 20,000 [[megawatts]] by 2020, at an estimated cost of 120 billion Chinese yuan ($17.5 billion). The project is being built by more than 20 developers in two localities in [[Guazhou County]] and also near [[Yumen City]].<ref name=reu>[https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5771IP20090808 China Starts Building First 10-GW Mega Wind Farm] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229230350/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5771IP20090808 |date=2010-12-29 }}, ''[[Reuters]]''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windpowermonthly.com/news/1016805/Chinas-Jiuquan-wind-farm-speeds-construction/|title=China's Jiuquan wind farm speeds up construction|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301051721/http://www.windpowermonthly.com/news/1016805/Chinas-Jiuquan-wind-farm-speeds-construction/|archive-date=1 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{wide image|Gansu.Guazhou.windfarm.croped.jpg|1000px|A small part of the huge Guazhou wind turbine farm}}\n\n== Construction phases ==\n[[File:Wind Farm In Gansu PRC.JPG|thumb|A wind turbine in the wind farm]]\n[[File:Guazhou.champs \u00e9oliennes.2.jpg|thumb|Gansu Wind Farm]]\nThe project is divided into multiple phases. The first 3,800 MW phase consisted of eighteen 200 MW wind farms and two 100 MW wind farms. The second 8,000 MW phase consists of forty 200 MW wind farms. The planned capacity is 5,160 MW by 2010, 12,710 MW by 2015 and 20,000 MW in 2020.<ref name=reu />\n\nIn 2008, construction began on a 750 kV AC power line to carry electricity from the wind farm,<ref>Peter Fairley. [http://www.technologyreview.com/energy/23460/page2/ China's Potent Wind Potential] ''[[Technology Review]]'', September 14, 2009.</ref> and construction of the wind farms themselves started in August 2009.<ref name=reu /> Power in 2012 was being purchased for 0.54 yuan per kWh, compared with electricity from coal fired powerplants at 0.3 yuan per kWh.<ref name=\"Guardian-2012.03.19\">Watts, Jonathan & Huang, Cecily. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/mar/19/china-windfarms-renewable-energy Winds Of Change Blow Through China As Spending On Renewable Energy Soars] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203225721/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/mar/19/china-windfarms-renewable-energy |date=2016-12-03 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', March 19, 2012, revised on March 20, 2012. Retrieved January 4, 2012.</ref> Since operations began, some 6.26 billion kWh has been generated as of October 31, 2011 with 5.96 billion kWh of that produced in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2011/11/02/5902457.htm|title=Wind power generation from Jiuquan base hits 6.26 bln kwh by end-Oct.|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528182208/http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2011/11/02/5902457.htm|archive-date=28 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010 officials announced the completion of the project's first phase, involving the installation of over 3,500 wind turbines with an installed capacity of approximately 5,160 MW according to Wang Jianxin, director of the Jiuquan Development and Reform Commission.<ref name=\"CD-2010.11.04\">[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/bizchina/2010-11/04/content_11502951.htm Xinhua: Jiuquan Wind Power Base Completes First Stage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107133402/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/bizchina/2010-11/04/content_11502951.htm |date=2010-11-07 }}, ''[[Xinhua News Agency]]'', November 4, 2010. Retrieved from ChinaDaily.com.cn website January 3, 2013.</ref> Total installed capacity rose to approximately 6,000 MW in March 2012\u2014roughly equivalent to the United Kingdom's entire wind power capacity at that time.\n\n==Coordinated control centre==\nOn March 1, 2012, a \"wind power coordinated control system\" was implemented to adjust the output of the 18 wind farms of the Gansu Wind Farm Project, which total 10&nbsp;GW, to meet the needs of the transmission grid, which is limited to 1.5&nbsp;GW. This permitted the production of 1&nbsp;GWh more per day than previously, and greatly improves the system's stability.<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeccomposites.com/news/composites-news/china-northwest-grid-wind-electricity-coordinated-control-system|title=China northwest grid wind electricity coordinated control system|publisher=|access-date=28 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528181128/http://www.jeccomposites.com/news/composites-news/china-northwest-grid-wind-electricity-coordinated-control-system|archive-date=28 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCurtailment of wind turbine operations is a first order method for dealing with the [[intermittent power source|intermittency]] of wind, but normally loses available output when the power grid's transmission capacity has been reached. Other methods involve either added local industrial usage or added local storage capacity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy10osti/47187.pdf |title=The Role Of Energy Storage With Renewable Electricity Generation |access-date=2012-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916224824/http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy10osti/47187.pdf |archive-date=2012-09-16 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ewp.rpi.edu/hartford/users/papers/engr/ernesto/farrew2/Project/research/1D543506d01.pdf |title=Management of variable electricity loads in wind e Hydrogen systems: The case of a Spanish wind farm |access-date=2012-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072531/http://www.ewp.rpi.edu/hartford/users/papers/engr/ernesto/farrew2/Project/research/1D543506d01.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Demand and utilization==\nWith local-government favoritism toward coal and inadequate long-distance transmission capacity, Gansu \"now has some of the highest rates of underutilization in the wind sector in China\". [[National Development and Reform Commission#National Energy Administration|National Energy Administration]] statistics showed 39 percent of wind capacity in 2015 in Jiuquan was wasted.<ref name=nyt/>\n\nAs of 2017, Gansu is far from full capacity and the wind farm is producing less than half of its full potential. The two main reasons why this is happening is that Gansu is located far from the major Chinese cities and that there is a lack of demand for wind energy in China.<ref name=nyt>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/15/world/asia/china-gansu-wind-farm.html|title=It Can Power a Small Nation. But This Wind Farm in China Is Mostly Idle.|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Javier C.|date=2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202152938/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/15/world/asia/china-gansu-wind-farm.html|archive-date=2017-12-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Gansu wind farm sits along the [[Gobi desert]] where there are extremely high winds. However, this location is about a thousand miles from China\u2019s high density port cities that would serve as the biggest consumer of this energy.<ref name=nyt/>\nThere is a lack of enough infrastructure and transmission lines that would allow the energy to flow into the cities.\nThere is still also little demand for wind power in China compared to coal. Although China\u2019s central government is actively trying to reduce its emissions and build its clean energy sector, the local governments still push coal on their local industries because it creates more economic output and because the coal is mined locally, which helps local coal companies.<ref name=nyt/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|China|Weather|Renewable energy|Energy}}}}\n* [[List of largest power stations]]\n* [[List of onshore wind farms]]\n* [[List of power stations in China]]\n* [[Megaproject]]\n* [[Wind power in China]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wind power in China}}\n\n[[Category:Wind farms in China]]\n[[Category:Engineering projects]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDemand and utilization:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gansu_Wind_Farm"}
